ttribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}}s:4:\"item\";a:10:{i:0;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:51:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:57:\"How to Setup a Free Business Email Address (in 5 Minutes)\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:63:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-setup-a-free-business-email-address/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:71:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-setup-a-free-business-email-address/#respond\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Thu, 11 Apr 2019 12:00:22 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:4:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:19:\"WordPress Tutorials\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:5:\"email\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:14:\"business email\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:8:\"bluehost\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:29:\"https://wpforms.com/?p=427305\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:595:\"<p>Are you wondering how you can create a free professional email address for your business? Then you&#8217;re in the right place. A business email address builds trust among your customers as compared to the generic ones. Hence, it&#8217;s always recommended to use them for your brand. In this article, we&#8217;ll show how you can set [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-setup-a-free-business-email-address/\">How to Setup a Free Business Email Address (in 5 Minutes)</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:18:\"Sandipan Mukherjee\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:29258:\"<p>Are you wondering how you can create a free professional email address for your business? Then you&#8217;re in the right place. A business email address builds trust among your customers as compared to the generic ones. Hence, it&#8217;s always recommended to use them for your brand.</p>\n<p>In this article, we&#8217;ll show how you can set up a free business email address in 5 minutes.</p>\n<h3>What Is a Business Email Address?</h3>\n<p>A business email address is a professional looking email address that has your business domain name after @ instead of Gmail, Yahoo, or Outlook.</p>\n<p>Let&#8217;s explain it with the help of an example.</p>\n<p>Say, John Doe wants to create an email address for his business ABC limited. So, the professional email address of John Doe should be johndoe@abclimited.com and not something like johndoe.abclimited@gmail.com.</p>\n<p>But do you really need a business email address? The short answer is Yes. Here are some of the reasons why:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>It&#8217;s brandable and easy to remember.</li>\n<li>It looks professional.</li>\n<li>Customers trust business emails more than the generic ones.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>How to Create Your Business Email Address</h3>\n<p>Before we get to the &#8220;how&#8221;, first let&#8217;s talk about what we need to get started.</p>\n<p>The most important thing that you need is a domain name. For those who don&#8217;t know, a domain name is the address of your website. For example, when you type google.com in the address bar of your web browser, you&#8217;re directed to the homepage of Google. So google.com is a domain name.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-432698\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/domain-name.png\" alt=\"Domain Name\" width=\"562\" height=\"199\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/domain-name.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/domain-name-300x106.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Apart from a domain name, you may also have a live website. But that&#8217;s not a requirement for creating your professional email account.</p>\n<p>Now, if you do a quick search on Google, you&#8217;ll find many ways using which you can create a business email. However, you should be careful with this approach as you may end up losing your important data.</p>\n<p>With reliability and security in mind, we&#8217;ll share two methods with you in this article using which you can create your business email address.</p>\n<p>So without further ado, let&#8217;s get started with the first method.</p>\n<h3>Create a Business Email Address using Bluehost</h3>\n<p>Though it&#8217;s not a requirement to have a website for your business email, it&#8217;s certainly recommended to have one. Why? Because a website is the best way to promote your brand online.</p>\n<p>To <a href=\"https://www.wpbeginner.com/guides/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">start a website</a> for your business, you need two things: a domain name and a web hosting account.</p>\n<p>We already explained what a domain name is.</p>\n<p>But what is a web host? Well, it&#8217;s the place where your website files are situated. And the good news is most web hosting companies provide free business email service to their customers.</p>\n<p>Normally, a domain name will cost you $14.99 per year, whereas the price of the web hosting service starts from $7.99 per month.</p>\n<p>We know it can be a lot for a startup or a single business owner.</p>\n<p>That&#8217;s why we recommend <a title=\"Bluehost\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/refer/bluehost/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Bluehost</a> for starting a website. Bluehost is one of the oldest web hosting companies and it&#8217;s also recommended by WordPress.org.</p>\n<p>You can <a href=\"https://www.isitwp.com/hosting-reviews/bluehost-review/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">purchase their service</a> starting at $2.75 per month and also get a free domain. Not only that, but they&#8217;ll also provide free professional email service with all their plans. Isn&#8217;t that great?</p>\n<p>So let&#8217;s start the step by step process.</p>\n<h3>Step 1: Get Started</h3>\n<p>First of all, go to the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/refer/bluehost/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Bluehost website</a> to get things started. We&#8217;ll sign up for their hosting service and also register a domain name for our business.</p>\n<p>So click on the <strong>Get Started Now</strong> button to select a hosting plan.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/refer/bluehost/\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-427452\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/bluehost-web-hosting.png\" alt=\"Bluehost Web Hosting\" width=\"562\" height=\"355\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/bluehost-web-hosting.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/bluehost-web-hosting-300x190.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></a></p>\n<p>Bluehost offers three hosting packages to its customers: Basic, Plus, and Choice Plus. All these plans provide tons of features including free email service and a free domain.</p>\n<p>In most cases, the Basic and Plus plans are suitable for most bloggers, startups, and small businesses. And you can always upgrade to a higher plan later.</p>\n<p>So choose a plan as per your needs and then click on <strong>Select</strong> to proceed to the next step.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-432613\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/bluehost-hosting-plan.png\" alt=\"Bluehost hosting plan\" width=\"562\" height=\"330\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/bluehost-hosting-plan.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/bluehost-hosting-plan-300x176.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>In the next page, you&#8217;ll have the option to register your free domain name.</p>\n<p>A domain name represents your business, so make sure you use your brand or company name as your domain name. You may read <a href=\"https://www.wpbeginner.com/beginners-guide/tips-and-tools-to-pick-the-best-domain-for-your-blog/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">this guide on how to choose a domain name</a> for more information.</p>\n<p>So enter your preferred name in the text box, select a <a href=\"https://www.wpbeginner.com/beginners-guide/should-you-choose-a-new-domain-extension-for-your-website/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">domain extension</a>, and click <strong>Next</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-432615\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/register-domain-name-for-free.png\" alt=\"Register domain name for free\" width=\"562\" height=\"287\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/register-domain-name-for-free.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/register-domain-name-for-free-300x153.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>If your preferred domain name is not available or already registered, Bluehost will suggest some alternative names.</p>\n<p>You can also <a href=\"https://www.nameboy.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">search for some variations</a> of your business name, but make sure you don&#8217;t use hyphens (-) and numbers in your domain name.</p>\n<p>Once a domain name is available for registration, you&#8217;ll be taken to the last step.</p>\n<p>Here you&#8217;ll have to provide various information to Bluehost so that they can create your account. The form on this page is divided into 4 parts: account information, package information, package extras, and payment information.</p>\n<p>While account information asks for personal details like name, address, phone number, and email address, package information lets you select the account plan.</p>\n<p>As far as package extras are concerned, we recommend you to uncheck all the options. You can always purchase them later if you need them.</p>\n<p>Finally, provide your payment information to purchase your Bluehost hosting account. If you want to pay using PayPal, then click on <strong>More payment options</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-432622\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/bluehost-payment-options.png\" alt=\"Bluehost payment options\" width=\"562\" height=\"263\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/bluehost-payment-options.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/bluehost-payment-options-300x140.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Once done, click on the checkbox to accept the terms and conditions, and then click <strong>submit</strong>.</p>\n<p>Congratulations! You&#8217;ve successfully created your hosting account. You&#8217;ll now receive a welcome email from Bluehost with important details including your cPanel login credentials.</p>\n<p><strong>Note</strong>: cPanel is the place where you can manage your domain name, hosting, and email accounts.</p>\n<h3>Step 2: Create Your Business Email Address</h3>\n<p>Now that we&#8217;ve registered our domain name, its time to create a professional email address for our business.</p>\n<p>So head over to your <a href=\"https://my.bluehost.com/web-hosting/cplogin\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Bluehost account</a> and click on <strong>Email &amp; Office</strong>, present in the left sidebar. A page will open up showing all the domain names you have in your account.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-427473\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/bluehost-email-office.png\" alt=\"Bluehost Email Office\" width=\"562\" height=\"194\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/bluehost-email-office.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/bluehost-email-office-300x104.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Whether you&#8217;ve got a single domain or multiple ones, click <strong>Manage </strong>once you find your business domain name on this page.</p>\n<p>Next, click on the <strong>Create</strong> button, present on the right side of your screen, to open the &#8220;Create an Email Account&#8221; page.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-427480\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/create-a-free-business-email-address.png\" alt=\"Create a free business email address\" width=\"562\" height=\"381\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/create-a-free-business-email-address.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/create-a-free-business-email-address-300x203.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Here, you&#8217;ll see a simple form asking for a new username and password.</p>\n<p>Your username in most cases should be your name, something like johndoe or john. However, you can also create an email address for your staff or department. Whatever the case may be, make sure the username is short and sweet.</p>\n<p>Also, don&#8217;t forget to enter a strong password. You can also use the <strong>Generate</strong> button to get a randomly generated password. Once done, go to the bottom of the page to click <strong>Create</strong>.</p>\n<p>That&#8217;s it! You&#8217;ve created your first professional email address for your brand. Repeat the same process for creating more accounts.</p>\n<h3>Step 3: Access Your Email Account</h3>\n<p>The next important thing is to access our inbox for sending and reading emails.</p>\n<p>To do that, you&#8217;ve to go to your Bluehost dashboard and then click on <strong>Email &amp; Office</strong>. Next, find your domain name and click <strong>Manage</strong>.</p>\n<p>Here you&#8217;ll see your newly created email address.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-427484\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/bluehost-check-email.png\" alt=\"Bluehost Check email\" width=\"562\" height=\"105\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/bluehost-check-email.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/bluehost-check-email-300x56.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Now click on <strong>Check Email</strong> to access your inbox. This will take you to a new page and will ask you to choose a webmail application.</p>\n<p>Select any one of them to open the inbox of your email account. You can now compose a mail, read your new emails, or even delete the existing ones.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-427485\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/webmail-application.png\" alt=\"webmail application\" width=\"562\" height=\"146\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/webmail-application.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/webmail-application-300x78.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Along with the above method, you can also use an email application like Microsoft Outlook 2010 for Windows to check your emails.</p>\n<h3>Setup a Business Email Address using G Suite</h3>\n<p>Before we start, you should know that this method is not free. However, <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/refer/gsuite/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">G Suite</a> offers tons of features and hence, we decided to include it in this article.</p>\n<p>Most importantly, G Suite is a product of Google and hence, you&#8217;ll be able to use Gmail&#8217;s interface for managing your business email account.</p>\n<p>The basic plan of <a title=\"GSuite\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/refer/gsuite/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">G Suite</a> costs $5 per month for each user. It offers 30 GB of space in Google Drive to every user and allows them to access Gmail, Docs, SpreadSheet, Slides, Calendar, and Video conferencing.</p>\n<p>Also, it comes with a 14-days free trial option. So, you can easily try their service first and then decide whether to continue or not.</p>\n<p>Anyways, let&#8217;s get started with the process of setting up your business email address using G Suite.</p>\n<h3>Step 1: Get Started</h3>\n<p>It&#8217;s time to get our hands dirty, so head over to the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/refer/gsuite/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">G Suite website</a>.</p>\n<p>Here you&#8217;ll find two plans: Basic and Business. For the time being, we recommend you to start with the basic plan. You can always upgrade to the business plan later.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/refer/gsuite/\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-427511\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/gsuite-plans.png\" alt=\"G Suite Plans\" width=\"562\" height=\"174\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/gsuite-plans.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/gsuite-plans-300x93.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></a></p>\n<p>So click on <strong>Get Started</strong> to proceed to the next page and start the setup wizard.</p>\n<p>First of all, you&#8217;ll have to provide some details like your business name, country, and the number of employees you&#8217;ve in your company. If you&#8217;re a single business owner, then you can select <strong>Just You</strong>. Once done, click on <strong>Next</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-432582\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/gsuite-business-info.png\" alt=\"G Suite business info\" width=\"562\" height=\"488\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/gsuite-business-info.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/gsuite-business-info-300x260.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Whether you selected one person or more than that, you need an administrator account to manage everything including users and payments.</p>\n<p>That&#8217;s why you need to provide some personal details like your name and current email address. This will create a G Suite admin account.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-432584\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/gsuite-personal-details.png\" alt=\"G Suite personal details\" width=\"562\" height=\"353\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/gsuite-personal-details.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/gsuite-personal-details-300x188.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>In the next step, the setup wizard will ask whether you already have a registered domain name for your business or not.</p>\n<p>In case you don&#8217;t have a domain, you can click on <strong>No, I need One</strong> to purchase a new domain name from Google. However, you should note that you&#8217;ll be charged $14.99 per year.</p>\n<p><strong>Pro Tip</strong>: You can get a free domain name with every <a title=\"Bluehost\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/refer/bluehost/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Bluehost web hosting</a> plan.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-432585\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/do-you-have-a-business-domain-name.png\" alt=\"Do you have a business domain name\" width=\"562\" height=\"220\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/do-you-have-a-business-domain-name.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/do-you-have-a-business-domain-name-300x117.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Anyways, we&#8217;ll assume that you already have a domain name. So, click on <strong>Yes, I have One I Can Use</strong> and enter your domain name in the next step.</p>\n<p>G Suite wizard will check whether the domain name is valid or not and then will ask if you want to continue with the same.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-432586\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/enter-business-domain-name.png\" alt=\"Enter Business Domain Name\" width=\"562\" height=\"321\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/enter-business-domain-name.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/enter-business-domain-name-300x171.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Next, you&#8217;ll be asked to select a username for your business email. You can choose your first name, last name, or a combination of both.</p>\n<p>Also, select a strong password and <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-build-a-spam-free-contact-form-without-captcha/\">prove that you&#8217;re not a robot</a>. Once done, click on <strong>Agree and Create Account</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-432589\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/create-a-gsuite-admin-account.png\" alt=\"Create a G Suite admin account\" width=\"562\" height=\"477\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/create-a-gsuite-admin-account.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/create-a-gsuite-admin-account-300x255.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>That&#8217;s it! You&#8217;ve created your G Suite account.</p>\n<p>But your job is half done. Click on <strong>Go to Setup</strong> to proceed to the next step where we&#8217;ll show how to create accounts for other users.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-432590\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/gsuite-business-account-created.png\" alt=\"G Suite business account created\" width=\"562\" height=\"224\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/gsuite-business-account-created.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/gsuite-business-account-created-300x120.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<h3>Step 2: Add People to Your G Suite Account</h3>\n<p>To add new user accounts other than the admin account, click <strong>Start</strong> to begin the process.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-432592\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/add-user-accounts-gsuite.png\" alt=\"Add user accounts to G Suite\" width=\"562\" height=\"245\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/add-user-accounts-gsuite.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/add-user-accounts-gsuite-300x131.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Now add details like first name, last name, and username and click <strong>Add</strong> to create a new account. Repeat the same process for the rest of your team members.</p>\n<p>Once you&#8217;re done, tick the checkbox that says &#8220;I added all user email addresses&#8221; and click <strong>Next </strong>to proceed to the domain verification process.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-432593\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/create-user-account.png\" alt=\"Create User Account\" width=\"562\" height=\"335\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/create-user-account.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/create-user-account-300x179.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>If you need a business email just for your own use, then tick that checkbox and proceed to the next step without creating another account. And don&#8217;t worry, you can always create more user accounts later if you want.</p>\n<h3>Step 3: Verify Your Domain Name</h3>\n<p>Though you&#8217;ve created your professional email address, it won&#8217;t work until and unless you connect your G Suite account to your domain name. And to do that, you&#8217;ll have to first verify that the domain name belongs to you.</p>\n<p>G Suite offers different methods using which you can complete this step.</p>\n<p>However, if you already have a WordPress website, then you can verify your domain by adding a meta tag in the head section of your homepage and that too with the help of a plugin.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-432594\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/verify-domain-using-meta-tag.png\" alt=\"Verify Domain using Meta Tag\" width=\"562\" height=\"209\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/verify-domain-using-meta-tag.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/verify-domain-using-meta-tag-300x112.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>We&#8217;ll use the free <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/insert-headers-and-footers/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Insert Headers and Footers</a> plugin to add the meta tag.</p>\n<p>Go to <strong>Plugins</strong> » <strong>Add New</strong> on your WordPress admin panel and search for <strong>Insert Headers and Footers </strong>in the search bar. Once you find it, install and active it.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-427571\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/insert-headers-and-footers-plugin.png\" alt=\"Insert Headers and Footers plugin\" width=\"562\" height=\"369\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/insert-headers-and-footers-plugin.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/insert-headers-and-footers-plugin-300x197.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Now go to <strong>Settings</strong> » <strong>Insert Headers and Footers</strong> and paste the G Suite verification meta tag in the <strong>Scripts in Header</strong> section. Once done, click on the <strong>Save</strong> button.</p>\n<p>Next, head over to your G Suite wizard and check the <strong>I added the meta tag to my homepage</strong> option to proceed to the final setup process.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-432595\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/setup-email-meta-tag.png\" alt=\"Setup Email Meta Tag\" width=\"562\" height=\"148\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/setup-email-meta-tag.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/setup-email-meta-tag-300x79.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<h3>Step 4: Add MX Records</h3>\n<p>Now it&#8217;s time to add MX records to your domain&#8217;s DNS.</p>\n<p>Wait! What is an MX record? An MX or Mail Exchanger record specifies where the email server is for a particular domain so that all the emails can be sent to that server.</p>\n<p>In simple words, you have to make some changes (add MX records) to the settings of your domain so that your emails can be directed to your G Suite account.</p>\n<p>So first of all, open the control panel of your domain registrar or web host and then, go back to the G Suite setup wizard to click <strong>I have opened the control panel for my domain</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-427619\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/gsuite-mx-records.png\" alt=\"G Suite MX records\" width=\"562\" height=\"426\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/gsuite-mx-records.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/gsuite-mx-records-300x227.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>G Suite will now show you some MX records which you need to add to your domain&#8217;s DNS. Whatever your case may be, the process of adding MX record is similar for every domain registrar or web host.</p>\n<p>Let&#8217;s show you how to do this on our Bluehost account.</p>\n<p>Go to your Bluehost dashboard and click on <strong>Domain</strong>. Here you&#8217;ll find all your registered domains. So click the checkbox of the domain name for which you want to add MX records.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-427615\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/bluehost-domain-management.png\" alt=\"Bluehost domain management\" width=\"562\" height=\"217\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/bluehost-domain-management.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/bluehost-domain-management-300x116.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>On the right side of the page, you&#8217;ll find the option <strong>DNS Zone Editor</strong>. Click on <strong>Manage</strong> to continue.</p>\n<p>Here you&#8217;ll have to enter all the 5 MX records as provided by G Suite. Let&#8217;s start by adding the first entry:</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-432596\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/add-mx-records.png\" alt=\"Add MX Records\" width=\"562\" height=\"274\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/add-mx-records.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/add-mx-records-300x146.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Make sure you do this for each MX record and click <strong>Add Record</strong>. If successfully added, the new records will be present under the MX (Mail Exchanger) section on the same page (scroll down to check).</p>\n<p>Once you&#8217;ve added all of them, go to the G Suite wizard and click <strong>I created the new MX records</strong>.</p>\n<p>Next, you&#8217;ll have to delete any existing MX records you had earlier. So go to the DNS zone of your domain and delete all the MX records except the new ones.</p>\n<p>Click on <strong>I have deleted existing MX records</strong> and then on <strong>I saved the MX records</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-432597\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/verify-domain-and-set-up-email.png\" alt=\"Verify domain and set up email\" width=\"562\" height=\"394\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/verify-domain-and-set-up-email.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/verify-domain-and-set-up-email-300x210.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Finally, click on <strong>Verify Domain and Set up Email</strong> to complete the verification and setup process.</p>\n<h3>Step 5: Access your Email Account</h3>\n<p>In the last step, we&#8217;ve successfully added the MX records and also verified our domain name. So, our business email address is now ready for use.</p>\n<p>But you might be wondering where the option to make payment is. Well, as stated earlier, G Suite comes with a 14 days free trial and hence, you can start paying after that period.</p>\n<p>To manage the user accounts, payments, and more, you can visit the <a href=\"https://admin.google.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">G Suite Admin panel</a> and do the needful.</p>\n<p>How can you access your G Suite email inbox? You can either go to the <a href=\"https://www.google.com/gmail/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Gmail website</a> or use the Gmail app on your phone. As simple as that!</p>\n<h3>Conclusion</h3>\n<p>That&#8217;s it! You&#8217;ve now created a professional email address for your business.</p>\n<p>Do you want to know how to brand your emails and make them look more professional? Check out these <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/email-branding-tips-for-small-businesses/\">6 email branding tips for small businesses</a>.</p>\n<p>If you liked this article, then please follow us on <a href=\"http://twitter.com/easywpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Twitter</a> and <a href=\"http://facebook.com/wpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Facebook</a> to get updates from our blog.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-setup-a-free-business-email-address/\">How to Setup a Free Business Email Address (in 5 Minutes)</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:68:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-setup-a-free-business-email-address/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:1;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:57:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:57:\"Stripe vs PayPal – Which One Is Better? (Pros and Cons)\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:57:\"https://wpforms.com/stripe-vs-paypal-which-one-is-better/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:65:\"https://wpforms.com/stripe-vs-paypal-which-one-is-better/#respond\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Mon, 08 Apr 2019 12:00:50 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:6:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"Marketing\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:6:\"stripe\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:10:\"order form\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:6:\"paypal\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:4;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:16:\"form integration\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:5;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:17:\"make money online\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:29:\"https://wpforms.com/?p=426175\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:583:\"<p>Are you trying to decide between Stripe vs PayPal to collect payments or donations on your website? Because Stripe and PayPal are the most popular online payment solutions, your decision on picking a payment provider for your site probably comes down to these two. This article will compare the pros and cons of both payment [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/stripe-vs-paypal-which-one-is-better/\">Stripe vs PayPal &#8211; Which One Is Better? (Pros and Cons)</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:12:\"Lisa Gennaro\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:20741:\"<p>Are you trying to decide between Stripe vs PayPal to collect payments or donations on your website?</p>\n<p>Because Stripe and PayPal are the most popular online payment solutions, your decision on picking a payment provider for your site probably comes down to these two.</p>\n<p>This article will compare the pros and cons of both payment gateways, so you can decide if Stripe vs PayPal works better for you to accept online payments for your business.</p>\n<h3>Stripe vs PayPal Compared</h3>\n<p>Stripe and PayPal are two of the most well-known payment solutions that let you collect money online. To collect funds from your site visitors through your website, your business needs a payment provider. If you want to know the differences between Stripe vs PayPal, you have to look at the pros and cons of both.</p>\n<h3>What Exactly Does Stripe Do?</h3>\n<p>Stripe is an online payment service that lets people accept and send money over the internet, and its popularity is growing in the eCommerce world. Stripe is especially liked by code-savvy people or teams with in-house programmers because of its customizable development tools. It&#8217;s a popular pick for small businesses but is also used by companies like Pinterest, Lyft, Blue Apron, and TaskRabbit.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-426208\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/stripe-vs-paypal-for-nonprofits.jpg\" alt=\"stripe-vs-paypal-for-nonprofits\" width=\"562\" height=\"386\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/stripe-vs-paypal-for-nonprofits.jpg 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/stripe-vs-paypal-for-nonprofits-300x206.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<h3>What Exactly Does PayPal Do?</h3>\n<p>PayPal is a payment solution that lets users make and receive payments online, and it’s very well-known. PayPal claims to have over 267 million customer accounts, including over 21 million merchants. Nearly everyone has a PayPal account these days and it&#8217;s easily one of the most recognizable names in the eCommerce payments industry.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-426236\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/stripe-vs-paypal-pros-and-cons-1.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"562\" height=\"361\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/stripe-vs-paypal-pros-and-cons-1.jpg 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/stripe-vs-paypal-pros-and-cons-1-300x193.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<h3>Who Uses Stripe and PayPal?</h3>\n<p>Collecting payments on your website is easy with <a href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a> for many types of businesses, including:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Freelancers</li>\n<li>Brick-and-mortar shops who want to also sell online</li>\n<li>Nonprofits <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-nonprofit-donation-form/\">collecting donations</a></li>\n<li>eCommerce companies</li>\n<li>Agencies</li>\n<li>Online marketplaces</li>\n<li>Entrepreneurs</li>\n<li>And more</li>\n</ul>\n<p>To get started creating a simple order form right away, read our tutorial on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-simple-order-form-in-wordpress/\">how to create a simple order form in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<h3>Stripe vs PayPal at a Glance</h3>\n<p>WPForms integrates with both <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/stripe-addon/\">Stripe</a> and <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/paypal-standard-addon/\">PayPal</a> for accepting payments, but you&#8217;ll still want to research the differences between the two. Let’s take a look at a summary snapshot of Stripe vs PayPal.</p>\n<table class=\"tableizer-table\">\n<thead>\n<tr class=\"tableizer-firstrow\">\n<th>Service</th>\n<th>Stripe</th>\n<th>PayPal Standard</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Fee per Transaction*</td>\n<td>2.9% + 30¢</td>\n<td>2.9% + 30¢</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Nonprofit Discount*</td>\n<td>2.2% + 30¢</td>\n<td>2.2% + 30¢</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Setup Costs or Monthly Fees</td>\n<td>No</td>\n<td>No</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Contract Required</td>\n<td>No</td>\n<td>No</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Micropayments (&lt;$10)</td>\n<td>Same Flat Rate</td>\n<td>5% + .05¢</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Recurring Billing</td>\n<td>Yes</td>\n<td>No</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Chargeback Fee</td>\n<td>$15</td>\n<td>$20</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Refunds</td>\n<td>No Fees Returned</td>\n<td>Fixed Fee Returned</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Customer Support</td>\n<td>Email, Help Center, 24/7 Phone &amp; Chat</td>\n<td>Email, Help Center, Phone &amp; Chat</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Ease of Use</td>\n<td>Easy</td>\n<td>Easy</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Ease of Setup</td>\n<td>Moderate</td>\n<td>Easy</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>PCI Compliance</td>\n<td>Yes</td>\n<td>Yes</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Countries Available</td>\n<td>32+</td>\n<td>200+</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Access to Funds Times</td>\n<td>2 Days (Average)</td>\n<td>Immediate</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Data Portability</td>\n<td>Yes</td>\n<td>No</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Online Invoicing</td>\n<td>Free for your first $1M in sales</td>\n<td>Free</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>In-Person Card Readers</td>\n<td>Paid</td>\n<td>Free &amp; Paid</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Payments Handled 100% on Your Site</td>\n<td>Yes</td>\n<td>No</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>*US-based only. Fees vary by country.</td>\n<td></td>\n<td></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<h3>Important Considerations When Choosing Stripe vs PayPal</h3>\n<p>There are some important things to compare when choosing Stripe vs PayPal:</p>\n<div class=\"alert alert-success\">Since this is a lengthy article, we&#8217;ve added a table of contents for easy navigation.</div>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#cost\">Cost</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#micropayments\">Micropayments</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#chargebacks\">Chargebacks/Refunds</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#customer-support\">Customer Support</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#ease-of-use\">Ease of Use</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#ease-of-setup\">Ease of Setup</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#security\">Security</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#availability\">Availability</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#access-to-funds-time\">Access to Funds Time</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#compatibility\">Compatibility</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#data-portability\">Data Portability</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#online-invoicing\">Online Invoicing</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#card-readers\">Card Readers</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#where-payments-are-handled\">Where Payments Are Handled</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Let&#8217;s take a deeper look at each factor:</p>\n<p id=\"cost\"><strong>Cost</strong></p>\n<p>Both Stripe and PayPal are very transparent about their fees, which is one of the reasons why they&#8217;re leaders in the online payments industry. Both Stripe and PayPal&#8217;s US fees per transaction are 2.9% + 30¢ and both offer plans with no setup costs, basic monthly fees, or contracts.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-427168\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/stripe-vs-paypal-vs-square.jpg\" alt=\"stripe-vs-paypal-vs-square\" width=\"562\" height=\"432\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/stripe-vs-paypal-vs-square.jpg 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/stripe-vs-paypal-vs-square-300x231.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-427175\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/paypal-vs-stripe-uk.jpg\" alt=\"paypal-vs-stripe-uk\" width=\"562\" height=\"409\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/paypal-vs-stripe-uk.jpg 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/paypal-vs-stripe-uk-300x218.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>So, with both Stripe and PayPal, your business is eligible for lower pricing if you hit a certain number in monthly sales. Stripe fees get lower at $80,000 per month and for PayPal it happens at a much lower sales volume of $3,000 per month.</p>\n<div class=\"alert alert-success\">Both companies offer nonprofit discounts at 2.2% + 30¢ for US fees.</div>\n<p id=\"micropayments\"><strong>Micropayments</strong></p>\n<p>If you&#8217;re processing transactions of less than $10, Stripe offers micropayment support with the same flat rate as your standard fee per transaction. Paypal&#8217;s micropayment rates are 5% + .05¢ per transaction.</p>\n<p id=\"chargebacks\"><strong>Chargebacks/Refunds</strong></p>\n<p>A chargeback is a charge reversal that happens when somebody contacts their bank and reports a transaction on their card that they don&#8217;t agree with or think is fraud. They exist to protect cardholders, but are sometimes over-utilized which can be frustrating since your business will pay a fee for each chargeback that happens.</p>\n<p>Stripe has a chargeback fee of $15, while PayPal&#8217;s chargeback fee is $20.</p>\n<p>Also, if your customer gets a refund, Stripe won&#8217;t return any processing fees to you. On the other hand, PayPal will return just the fixed fee, but not the percentage.</p>\n<p id=\"customer-support\"><strong>Customer Support</strong></p>\n<p>Stripe has several ways to get in touch when you have questions including a help center, social media, and chat support channels (with support reps or developers), plus phone and email support.</p>\n<p>PayPal has multiple ways to get answers to your questions from their customer support team like a community forum, a help center, and social media, plus email, live chat and phone support.</p>\n<p>Even with all these ways to get your questions answered, users still say that the quality of customer service from both Stripe and PayPal can vary from good to poor and is frustrating at times. However, Stripe recently added 24/7 access to both phone and chat support while PayPal&#8217;s support still goes dark at some hours of the day.</p>\n<p>Stripe has also added an option for paid Premium Support with extra features:</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/stripe-vs-paypal-premium-support-click.jpg\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-430468 size-full\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/stripe-standard-vs-premium-support-click.jpg\" alt=\"stripe-standard-vs-premium-support-click\" width=\"562\" height=\"480\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/stripe-standard-vs-premium-support-click.jpg 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/stripe-standard-vs-premium-support-click-300x256.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></a></p>\n<p id=\"ease-of-use\"><strong>Ease of Use</strong></p>\n<p>Both Stripe and PayPal are known for being super easy to use. Both companies have made it really simple for customers to pay online.</p>\n<p id=\"ease-of-setup\"><strong>Ease of Setup</strong></p>\n<p>Stripe is more customizable over PayPal. However,  to embed a feature like a <strong>Pay With Card</strong> button on your site, Stripe requires a bit more development knowledge and can sometimes be tricky for non-technical users. With WPForms, setup for both Stripe and PayPal is a breeze since they&#8217;re both available in our pre-built form templates with the Stripe and PayPal Standard Addons.</p>\n<p id=\"security\"><strong>Security</strong></p>\n<p>Both Stripe and PayPal&#8217;s services are PCI Complaint. In other words, they meet the strict standards of the Payment Card Industry and your cardholder data is stored securely.</p>\n<p id=\"availability\"><strong>Availability</strong></p>\n<p>PayPal is available is many more countries than Stripe. Currently, PayPal is offered in <a href=\"https://www.paypal.com/us/webapps/mpp/country-worldwide\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">200+ countries</a> while Stripe has just <a href=\"https://stripe.com/global\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">32+ countries</a> (and growing).</p>\n<p id=\"access-to-funds\"><strong>Access to Funds Time</strong></p>\n<p>Stripe will automatically deposit your funds into your bank account with a 2-day average payout time. On the other hand, your funds are available immediately in your PayPal account with PayPal Standard. However, PayPal averages a 2-4 day payout time when moving your funds from your PayPal account into your bank account.</p>\n<p id=\"compatibility\"><strong>Compatibility</strong></p>\n<p>You can use both Stripe and PayPal with WordPress, and both products are integrated with WPForms.</p>\n<p id=\"data-portability\"><strong>Data Portability</strong></p>\n<p>At some point, you may want to move all your data to another payment processor that is not Stripe or PayPal. This is known as Data Portability.</p>\n<p>Stripe values Data Portability, so they&#8217;ll help you move your credit card data in a PCI Compliant way.</p>\n<p>PayPal won&#8217;t give you this data if you try to switch processors, which can be a headache. For some people, it&#8217;s important to have the choice to be able to move their payment data if they want.</p>\n<p id=\"online-invoicing\"><strong>Online Invoicing</strong></p>\n<p>Stripe and PayPal both have customizable online invoicing. This is free with PayPal, and free with Stripe until you bill over $1 million. You may be surprised how quickly your sales add up. If your online store is doing poorly in sales, check out this <a href=\"https://optinmonster.com/ecommerce-optimization-guide/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">guide to eCommerce optimization</a> on our sister site that can help boost your revenue.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-427195\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/paypal-vs-stripe-australia.jpg\" alt=\"paypal-vs-stripe-australia\" width=\"562\" height=\"605\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/paypal-vs-stripe-australia.jpg 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/paypal-vs-stripe-australia-279x300.jpg 279w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-427196\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/stripe-vs-paypal-reddit.jpg\" alt=\"stripe-vs-paypal-reddit\" width=\"562\" height=\"438\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/stripe-vs-paypal-reddit.jpg 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/stripe-vs-paypal-reddit-300x234.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p id=\"card-readers\"><strong>Card Readers</strong></p>\n<p>If you&#8217;re a brick-and-mortar store adding an online presence and want to use the same payment processor for your storefront and your website, you can do just that with both Stripe and PayPal.</p>\n<p>PayPal has integrations into many popular Point of Sale systems, and both Stripe and PayPal offer their own physical card readers. PayPal will give you free card readers and also has paid card readers you can buy, while Stripe only offers paid card readers.</p>\n<p><strong>Where Payments Are Handled</strong></p>\n<p>It&#8217;s important to note that Stripe lets people pay you without ever leaving your website. PayPal requires people exit your website to sign in to a PayPal account before being redirected back to your site, which may be undesirable for you if you want to keep your branding consistent from start to finish during your customer&#8217;s buying process.</p>\n<p>On the other hand, this step may not bother some business owners as this is a fairly familiar process for many customers, but it&#8217;s a factor to consider.</p>\n<h3>Stripe Pros</h3>\n<p>Here are some of the benefits of using Stripe to collect money online:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Flat, predictable rates</li>\n<li>Easy for your customers to use</li>\n<li>Keep and move your customer data</li>\n<li>Customers never leave your site during the buying cycle</li>\n<li>Nonprofit discounts</li>\n<li>No contract required</li>\n<li>Lower chargeback fee ($15)</li>\n<li>24/7 support</li>\n<li>Multiple support options (help center, phone, live chat and email)</li>\n<li>Developer live chat support for complex issues</li>\n<li>PCI Compliant</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Stripe Cons</h3>\n<p>This solution might not be a perfect fit for everyone:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Isn’t as user-friendly to set up (The WPForms support team has you covered with this guide on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-install-and-use-the-stripe-addon-with-wpforms/\">how to install the Stripe Addon</a>)</li>\n<li>Not as well-known or a household name like PayPal</li>\n<li>Takes longer to access your money (2-day average)</li>\n<li>No fees returned with refunds</li>\n<li>Inconsistent support quality</li>\n<li>Available in fewer countries than PayPal</li>\n<li>Online invoicing only free until $1M in sales</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>PayPal Standard Pros</h3>\n<p>Let’s check out some benefits of using PayPal Standard for accepting payments on your website:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Flat, predictable rates</li>\n<li>Easy to setup an account</li>\n<li>Easy for your customers to use</li>\n<li>Integrations with some POS systems if you want to sell in person</li>\n<li>Customers are familiar with and trust PayPal</li>\n<li>Funds are available immediately in your PayPal account</li>\n<li>Nonprofit discounts</li>\n<li>No contract required</li>\n<li>Fixed fees returned with refunds</li>\n<li>Multiple support options (help center, phone, live chat and email)</li>\n<li>PCI Compliant</li>\n<li>Available in 200+ countries</li>\n<li>Free online invoicing</li>\n<li>Free card readers for your storefront</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>PayPal Standard Cons</h3>\n<p>Like most things, there are a few downsides to using PayPal Standard to collect payments on your website. Let’s take a look:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Can&#8217;t move all your customer data to another payment processor</li>\n<li>No Recurring Billing</li>\n<li>Redirects customers away from your website during the checkout process</li>\n<li>Higher chargeback fee ($25)</li>\n<li>Inconsistent support quality</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Stripe vs PayPal &#8211; Which One Is Better?</h3>\n<p>So which online payment gateway should you use?</p>\n<p>The answer depends on your business’ individual needs including your industry, the type of customers you have, and what you&#8217;re selling. One type of merchant may prefer to go with one payment solution over another.</p>\n<p>It&#8217;s also important to note that with WPForms, you don&#8217;t have to select just one payment solution to accept payments on your website.</p>\n<h3>You Can Use Both</h3>\n<p>To use both Stripe and PayPal, you’ll need to setup accounts with each company. This way, you can allow your visitors to select which one they want to use. Head over to our guide on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-allow-users-to-choose-a-payment-method-on-your-form/\">how to allow users to choose a payment method</a> to learn more.</p>\n<p>If you do this, keep in mind that your funds will be deposited to your bank account separately, which could cause extra administrative work. You&#8217;ll be spending more time dealing with both Stripe and PayPal if you&#8217;re using the two, so weigh all your options before deciding if this is the best route for you.</p>\n<p>With the simplicity of WPForms, even non-technical people can create beautiful order forms that accept payments or donations right on their WordPress site with our pre-built donation and order form templates. You can easily let users choose if they want to pay through either Stripe or PayPal in your forms.</p>\n<h3>Final Thoughts</h3>\n<p>Both Stripe and PayPal offer great features and major flexibility. Ultimately, which payment gateway you choose depends on your business&#8217; specific needs. Accepting payments in WordPress is super simple with <a href=\"http://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>. With our <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/stripe-addon/\">Stripe Addon</a> and <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/paypal-standard-addon/\">PayPal Standard Addon</a> features, you can easily collect payments and donations through the most popular online payment gateways directly on your website.</p>\n<p>And there you have it! You can now make an educated decision about whether Stripe vs PayPal will be a better fit for your business to collect payments or donations online, based on their individual pros and cons.</p>\n<p>Ready to create a form that accepts payments? Head over to our tutorial on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-simple-order-form-in-wordpress/\">how to create a simple order form in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>So, what are you waiting for? Get started with the most powerful <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/\">WordPress forms plugin</a> today.</p>\n<p>And don’t forget, if you like this article, then please follow us on <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/wpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Facebook</a> and <a href=\"http://twitter.com/easywpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Twitter</a>.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/stripe-vs-paypal-which-one-is-better/\">Stripe vs PayPal &#8211; Which One Is Better? (Pros and Cons)</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:62:\"https://wpforms.com/stripe-vs-paypal-which-one-is-better/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:2;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:51:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:56:\"7 Best WordPress LMS Plugins in 2019 (with Free Options)\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:47:\"https://wpforms.com/best-wordpress-lms-plugins/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:55:\"https://wpforms.com/best-wordpress-lms-plugins/#respond\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Thu, 04 Apr 2019 12:00:38 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:4:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"Showcases\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:17:\"WordPress plugins\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:12:\"free plugins\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:11:\"lms plugins\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:29:\"https://wpforms.com/?p=425434\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:581:\"<p>Are you looking for a Learning Management System (LMS) plugin for your WordPress website? Then you&#8217;re in the right place. Choosing the best LMS plugin will help you to create, manage, and sell online courses from your website without any hassle. In this article, we’ll compare the best WordPress LMS Plugins to make your decision [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/best-wordpress-lms-plugins/\">7 Best WordPress LMS Plugins in 2019 (with Free Options)</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:18:\"Sandipan Mukherjee\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:17503:\"<p>Are you looking for a Learning Management System (LMS) plugin for your WordPress website? Then you&#8217;re in the right place. Choosing the best LMS plugin will help you to create, manage, and sell online courses from your website without any hassle.</p>\n<p>In this article, we’ll compare the best WordPress LMS Plugins to make your decision easier.</p>\n<h3>What to Look For in a WordPress LMS Plugin?</h3>\n<p>Look: To start your own Udemy or Treehouse-like website, you need to enhance the functionality of your WordPress site. That’s where an LMS plugin comes in handy.</p>\n<p>Now, there are many LMS plugins out there and it&#8217;ll be difficult for you to choose the best one for your needs. So you need to first understand your requirements before selecting a particular plugin.</p>\n<p>Whatever your necessities may be, here are some of the most essential features to look for in your LMS plugin:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Ease to create and manage a course.</li>\n<li>Ability to monitor the progress of students.</li>\n<li>Can offer certificates and badges as incentives.</li>\n<li>Content dripping to schedule lessons.</li>\n<li>Built-in payment gateway support and monetization options.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Now that we know what the basic features should be, let’s get started with the list of the best LMS WordPress Plugins.</p>\n<h3>1. <a title=\"LearnDash\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/refer/learndash/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">LearnDash</a></h3>\n<p><a title=\"LearnDash\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/refer/learndash/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener nooperner\"><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-425445 size-full\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/learndash-lms-plugin.png\" alt=\"LearnDash LMS Plugin\" width=\"562\" height=\"265\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/learndash-lms-plugin.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/learndash-lms-plugin-300x141.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></a></p>\n<p>LearnDash is the most popular LMS WordPress plugin on the web. It can be useful for universities, professional training institutions, or anyone looking to create an eLearning platform.</p>\n<p>It comes with a drag and drop course builder that allows you to easily create multi-level courses and add lessons, assignments, and quizzes to them. You can also set prerequisites to guide your students on the right path.</p>\n<p>Want to schedule the lessons in your course? You can do that by making the lessons visible on a specific date or after a certain period. Also, you can notify your users automatically once the lessons are accessible to them.</p>\n<p>One of the features of LearnDash that needs special mention is Course Points. It allows your students to earn points once they complete a course. And they can use these points to unlock other courses you offer. Basically, it&#8217;s a <a href=\"https://optinmonster.com/gamification-in-marketing/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">gamification technique</a> that increases the engagement of the students on your website.</p>\n<p>Anyways, let’s take a look at some of the other features:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Award certificates to students once they complete a course.</li>\n<li>Add a timer to your lessons to prevent users from skipping them.</li>\n<li>Allow your students to track their course progress, print certificates, and more using their frontend profiles.</li>\n<li>Use free and premium addons to add extra features to your site.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Last but not least, LearnDash comes with a lot of monetization options including one-time purchase, membership, and course bundles. It also supports multiple payment gateways like PayPal, Stripe, and 2Checkout to make life easy for you.</p>\n<p><strong>Price</strong>: Starting from $159 per year for a single site.</p>\n<h3>2. <a title=\"LifterLMS\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/refer/lifterlms/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener nooperner\">Lifter LMS</a></h3>\n<p><a title=\"LifterLMS\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/refer/lifterlms/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener nooperner\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-425449\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/lifterlms-plugin.png\" alt=\"LifterLMS Plugin\" width=\"562\" height=\"254\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/lifterlms-plugin.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/lifterlms-plugin-300x136.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></a></p>\n<p>Lifter LMS is a simple yet powerful LMS plugin that comes with tons of useful features. Just like LearnDash, it offers a drag and drop course builder and thus, helps you to build multi-tier courses with audio, video, images, and text-based lessons.</p>\n<p>This plugin allows you to create multimedia quizzes for your students and set a maximum time limit to test their knowledge. You can also create assignments, set prerequisites, drip content, and offer downloadable material for offline learning.</p>\n<p>Do you want to start a multi-instructor platform? You can do that with the help of Lifter LMS. Not only that, but you can also assign multiple instructors to a single course. And the students can easily interact with the instructors using forums, lesson comments, timelines, and private coaching areas.</p>\n<p>While the basic features are included in the <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/lifterlms/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">free version of this plugin</a>, you can always enhance the functionality of your eLearning site by using different addons.</p>\n<p>For example, you can use the WPForms addon to create custom registration forms, collect testimonials, and <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/create-a-survey-form-in-wordpress-step-by-step/\">build online survey forms</a>. Or, you can collect payments using the PayPal extension, Authorize.net Payment Gateway, or Stripe extension.</p>\n<p>You can also integrate this plugin with the MailChimp extension to <a href=\"https://optinmonster.com/73-proven-and-simple-ways-to-grow-your-email-list/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">start building your email list</a>.</p>\n<p><strong>Price</strong>: Individual addons can be purchased for $99 per year, whereas the universal bundle is priced at $299 per year.</p>\n<h3>3. <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/learnpress/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">LearnPress</a></h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/learnpress/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-425453\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/learnpress-wordpress-plugin.png\" alt=\"LearnPress WordPress Plugin\" width=\"562\" height=\"245\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/learnpress-wordpress-plugin.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/learnpress-wordpress-plugin-300x131.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></a></p>\n<p>Looking for a free LMS plugin to start your eLearning site? LearnPress can be your friend. It&#8217;s a popular free plugin with more than 50,000 active installs and is suitable for those who are just starting out.</p>\n<p>It comes with a setup wizard to help you get started with basic things including currency selection and creation of important static pages. You can also create unlimited courses with multiple lessons and quizzes and make them available for free or sell them on your website</p>\n<p>LearnPress offers a number of free and premium addons to take your site to the next level.</p>\n<p>It can be integrated with the popular WooCommerce plugin. This allows you to add advanced payment features and use coupon system on your website. You can also use different payment gateways like PayPal, 2Checkout, Authorize.net, and Stripe to accept payments from your customers.</p>\n<p>Do you want the students to interact with the course instructors? You can achieve this with the help of the bbPress addon. You can also use the BuddyPress addon to set up students&#8217; profiles and let them connect with each other.</p>\n<p>Some of the other useful addons include offline payments, wishlist, content drip, and grade book.</p>\n<p><strong>Price</strong>: Free. However, you can buy the LearnPress Pro Bundle for $249 to get access to all the addons.</p>\n<h3>4. <a title=\"WP Courseware\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/refer/wp-courseware/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener nooperner\">WP Courseware</a></h3>\n<p><a title=\"WP Courseware\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/refer/wp-courseware/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener nooperner\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-425454\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wp-courseware-lms-plugin.png\" alt=\"WP Courseware LMS Plugin\" width=\"562\" height=\"329\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wp-courseware-lms-plugin.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wp-courseware-lms-plugin-300x176.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></a></p>\n<p>WP Courseware is a popular and feature-rich LMS solution. It offers a powerful drag and drop builder which makes course creation pretty simple.</p>\n<p>Like most LMS plugins, WP Courseware lets you create quizzes for your students.</p>\n<p>However, it comes with 2 types of quizzes: blocking and non-blocking. While blocking quizzes needs a student to get a minimum grade before they can move to the next lesson, non-blocking ones don&#8217;t have any such requirements.</p>\n<p>This plugin also has the ability to add a new user role called Instructor. In case you don&#8217;t know, WordPress comes with <a href=\"https://www.wpbeginner.com/beginners-guide/wordpress-user-roles-and-permissions/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">5 default user roles</a>. But you can also add custom roles if you want.</p>\n<p>Thus, you can invite different instructors to your eLearning site. The individual instructors will have the freedom to manage multiple courses and also enroll students to them.</p>\n<p>Anyways, let&#8217;s take a look at some of the other features:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Grade Books</strong>: View the progress of every student.</li>\n<li><strong>Certificates</strong>: Award downloadable certificates to students for completing a course.</li>\n<li><strong>Built-in Shopping Cart</strong>: Use PayPal or Stripe to sell your courses, either for a one-time fee or as a recurring subscription.</li>\n<li><strong>Free Courses</strong>: Offer free courses to prospective customers and <a href=\"https://optinmonster.com/beginners-guide-to-email-marketing/\" target=\"_blank\">build your email list</a>.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Lastly, you can also integrate WP Courseware with some of the most popular membership and eCommerce plugins like WooCommerce, Easy Digital Downloads, <a href=\"https://memberpress.com/\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">MemberPress</a>, and more.</p>\n<p><strong>Price</strong>: Starting from $129 for 2 sites.</p>\n<h3>5. <a title=\"Sensei\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/refer/sensei/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Sensei</a></h3>\n<p><a title=\"Sensei\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/refer/sensei/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener nooperner\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-425456\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/sensei-wordpress-lms-plugin.png\" alt=\"Sensei WordPress LMS Plugin\" width=\"562\" height=\"294\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/sensei-wordpress-lms-plugin.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/sensei-wordpress-lms-plugin-300x157.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></a></p>\n<p>Sensei is a premium learning management system plugin for WordPress and has been built by the team behind WooCommerce.</p>\n<p>It&#8217;s a simple and easy to use LMS plugin. You can easily create lessons, add quizzes, and set prerequisites. You can also integrate this plugin with WooCommerce and accept payments for your courses seamlessly.</p>\n<p>Though this plugin provides the basic features required for starting an online course, it still offers limited functionality as compared to some of the other LMS plugins in the market.</p>\n<p>However, you can always use some of the free and premium extensions like content drip, certificates, course progress, course participants, and more to expand the scope of this plugin.</p>\n<p><strong>Price</strong>: Starting from $129 for a single site.</p>\n<h3>6. <a href=\"https://premium.wpmudev.org/project/coursepress-pro/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">CoursePress Pro</a></h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://premium.wpmudev.org/project/coursepress-pro/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-425462\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/coursepress-pro-plugin.png\" alt=\"CoursePress Pro Plugin\" width=\"562\" height=\"267\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/coursepress-pro-plugin.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/coursepress-pro-plugin-300x143.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></a></p>\n<p>CoursePress Pro is a powerful LMS plugin that allows you to create, manage, and sell your courses online. It&#8217;s fully integrated with MarketPress and WooCommerce and comes with many built-in payment gateway options.</p>\n<p>This plugin offers some handy features for creating a Lynda-like site. It lets you create custom styled certificates for each course. You can also assess your students by creating different types of quizzes using the powerful quiz builder.</p>\n<p>Some of the other features of this plugin include:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Offer free and paid courses to your students.</li>\n<li>Ability to schedule lessons and send email notifications once they&#8217;re available.</li>\n<li>Built-in <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/best-email-marketing-service-providers-with-free-options/\">email marketing options</a>.</li>\n<li>Discussion board for students and teachers to interact.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>To use this plugin, you&#8217;ve to purchase the WPMU Dev membership for $49 per month. But you can always use their 30 days free trial to test the product before taking any decision.</p>\n<p><strong>Price</strong>: $49 per month for unlimited sites.</p>\n<h3>7. <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/namaste-lms/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Namaste! LMS</a></h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/namaste-lms/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-425472\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/namaste-lms-plugin.png\" alt=\"Namaste LMS Plugin\" width=\"562\" height=\"243\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/namaste-lms-plugin.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/namaste-lms-plugin-300x130.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></a></p>\n<p>Namaste! LMS is another free WordPress LMS plugin on our list. It also offers a premium version to add extra features to your site.</p>\n<p>Like every plugin on our list, Namaste! LMS allows you to create unlimited courses, lessons, and assignments. You can also give feedback to your students and award certificates to them for successfully completing the course.</p>\n<p>Let&#8217;s take a look at some important features of this plugin:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Support for payment gateways like Stripe and PayPal.</li>\n<li>Integrate with <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/watu/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Watu Quiz</a> plugin to create exams or quizzes.</li>\n<li>Use grade system to analyze the performance of each student.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Overall, Namaste! LMS is a lightweight plugin with limited options and hence, can be useful for creating a simple learning management platform.</p>\n<p><strong>Price</strong>: Free. But you can upgrade to Namaste! Pro with a one-time payment of $47.</p>\n<h3>Which LMS Plugin is Best for Your Needs?</h3>\n<p>After comparing the above LMS plugins, we can conclude that <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/refer/learndash/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">LearnDash</a> is a step ahead of its competitors.</p>\n<p>It offers some amazing features and useful addons to help you to build an amazing eLearning website. And unless you&#8217;re looking for a completely free plugin like LearnPress or Namaste! LMS, LearnDash can be a good choice for almost everyone.</p>\n<p>However, you should note one thing here: LearnDash doesn&#8217;t have the ability to create custom registration forms. But there&#8217;s no need to worry! You can always use WPForms to <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-user-registration-form-in-wordpress/\">build custom registration forms</a> on your website.</p>\n<p>Not using it so far? <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/\">Get started with WPForms today</a>!</p>\n<p>Anyways, we hope this article helped you to find the right LMS WordPress plugin for your website.</p>\n<p>If you want to start an online membership site, please check out our article on the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/best-wordpress-membership-plugins-compared/\">best WordPress membership plugins</a>.</p>\n<p>Also, please share this article on your favorite social media platform. And don&#8217;t forget to follow us on <a href=\"http://twitter.com/easywpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Twitter</a> and <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/wpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Facebook</a>.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/best-wordpress-lms-plugins/\">7 Best WordPress LMS Plugins in 2019 (with Free Options)</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:52:\"https://wpforms.com/best-wordpress-lms-plugins/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:3;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:57:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:58:\"How to Create a Complaint Form in WordPress (Step by Step)\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:77:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-complaint-form-in-wordpress-step-by-step/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:86:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-complaint-form-in-wordpress-step-by-step/#comments\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Mon, 01 Apr 2019 12:00:49 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:6:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:19:\"WordPress Tutorials\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:12:\"contact form\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:17:\"form notification\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:19:\"form templates pack\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:4;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:7:\"WPForms\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:5;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:14:\"complaint form\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:29:\"https://wpforms.com/?p=422666\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:606:\"<p>Need to create a complaint form in WordPress? Using WPForms is a really easy way to collect problems customers, employees and site visitors have had with your business to help make it better and improve customer or employee satisfaction. In this article, we’ll show you how to create a complaint form in WordPress using WPForms. [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-complaint-form-in-wordpress-step-by-step/\">How to Create a Complaint Form in WordPress (Step by Step)</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:12:\"Lisa Gennaro\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:16911:\"<p>Need to create a complaint form in WordPress? Using WPForms is a really easy way to collect problems customers, employees and site visitors have had with your business to help make it better and improve customer or employee satisfaction.</p>\n<p>In this article, we’ll show you how to create a complaint form in WordPress using WPForms.</p>\n<h3>What Is a Complaint Form?</h3>\n<p>A complaint form is a way to discover possible areas of improvements for your business while letting your site visitors feel heard by gathering important feedback directly on your website. Complaint forms can offer a private way for your audience to submit information online about issues with your products and services, as well as problems your employees may have.</p>\n<p>Also, you might consider creating a complaint form on your website to:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Get Feedback on Products and Services. </strong>A customer complaint form can provide an opportunity for you to figure out what’s bothering your customers about specific products and services. You’ll be able to find ways to help make your customers happier.</li>\n<li><strong>Create Strong Customer Relationships.</strong> A generic complaint form can help you better understand your customers while gathering useful tips to follow up on.</li>\n<li><strong>Make Employees Feel Better.</strong> Your employees want to be heard. Letting them start a discussion on their end can help you dive into possible workplace issues and start an important conversation.</li>\n<li><strong>Track Employee Behavior.</strong> A workplace complaint form can help you get a better idea of how employees treat each other, so you can stay on top of possible issues and keep your team on their best behavior.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Plus, creating a complaint form online is super simple when you use WPForms and the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/form-templates-pack-addon/\">Form Template Pack Addon</a>. This addon lets you choose from 100+ pre-built templates for every niche and industry, including a customer or employee complaint form template.</p>\n<p>Now, let’s take a look at how to create a complaint form in WordPress.</p>\n<h3>Step 1: Create a New Form in WordPress</h3>\n<p>Using WPForms is the easiest way to create a complaint web form in WordPress.</p>\n<p>The first thing you’ll need to do is install and activate the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms plugin.</a> For more details, follow this step by step guide on <a href=\"https://www.wpbeginner.com/beginners-guide/step-by-step-guide-to-install-a-wordpress-plugin-for-beginners/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">how to install a plugin in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>Next, you’ll need to install and activate the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/form-templates-pack-addon/\">Form Templates Pack addon</a>.</p>\n<p>To do this, go to <strong>WPForms</strong> » <strong>Addons</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-429580\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpforms-dashboard-addons.jpg\" alt=\"wpforms-dashboard-addons\" width=\"562\" height=\"533\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpforms-dashboard-addons.jpg 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpforms-dashboard-addons-300x285.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Next, use the <strong>Search Addons</strong> bar and type <strong>Form Templates Pack Addon</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-429600\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpforms-search-addons.jpg\" alt=\"wpforms-search-addons\" width=\"562\" height=\"429\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpforms-search-addons.jpg 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpforms-search-addons-300x229.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Now, click <strong>Install Addon</strong> and then <strong>Activate.</strong></p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-422675\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/form-templates-pack-addon.jpg\" alt=\"form-templates-pack-addon\" width=\"562\" height=\"215\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/form-templates-pack-addon.jpg 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/form-templates-pack-addon-300x115.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>At this point, you’ll need to create a new form.</p>\n<p>To begin, go to <strong>WPForms</strong> » <strong>Add New</strong>, and name your form. Then, scroll down to the <strong>Additional Templates</strong> section and type “complaint form” into the search bar.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-422676\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/complaint-form-template.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"562\" height=\"285\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/complaint-form-template.jpg 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/complaint-form-template-300x152.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Hover over Complaint Form and click the <strong>Create a Complaint Form</strong> button that appears.</p>\n<p>Once the pre-built complaint form template loads, you’ll notice most of the work is already done for you.</p>\n<p>You’ll see default form fields for:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>First and Last Name of the person submitting the complaint</li>\n<li>Email</li>\n<li>Phone</li>\n<li>Address</li>\n<li>Date / Time of incident</li>\n<li>Incident description</li>\n<li>Advice to resolve the issue</li>\n</ul>\n<p>This is the page where you&#8217;ll start to customize your form.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-429498\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpforms-complaint-form-default-fields.jpg\" alt=\"wpforms-complaint-form-default-fields\" width=\"562\" height=\"426\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpforms-complaint-form-default-fields.jpg 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpforms-complaint-form-default-fields-300x227.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>If you want to see the complaint form template in action, check out our <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/demo/complaint-form-demo/\">complaint form sample demo</a>.</p>\n<p>This complaint form format gives you a good starting point to customize your form depending on the type you&#8217;re creating. An employee complaint form may need to ask different questions than a customer complaint form, so you have the option to customize your complaint form.</p>\n<h3>Step 2: Customize Your Complaint Form Fields</h3>\n<p>To make any changes to a field, click on the field in the right-hand panel. You can also drag the fields to rearrange their order on your complaint form.</p>\n<p>For example, you may want to accept anonymous complaints through your form because you&#8217;re collecting general information and not planning on following up with people individually.</p>\n<p>To do so, simply click on the <strong>Name</strong> field and deselect the <strong>Required</strong> checkbox so that entering a name into the form when filling it out is optional.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-422685\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/complaint-form-required-checkbox.jpg\" alt=\"complaint-form-required-checkbox\" width=\"562\" height=\"430\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/complaint-form-required-checkbox.jpg 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/complaint-form-required-checkbox-300x230.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>You might also think about adding a <strong>Multiple Choice</strong> form field to your complaint form template so your users can pick the specific department or service they had a problem with.</p>\n<p>If your customer ran into an issue with your product and they want to send you an image with their complaint, you can add the <strong>File Upload</strong> form field to your complaint form.</p>\n<p>Complaints can be serious, so you can also give your visitors the option to receive a personal call from you or your customer support team at a time that works for them by adding another <strong>Date / Time</strong> field to your form. Using the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/zapier-addon/\">WPForms Zapier Addon</a>, you can integrate your complaint form with your Google Calendar to have the form information automatically added so you’ll never miss a scheduled call.</p>\n<p>When your complaint form looks the way you want it to, click <strong>Save.</strong></p>\n<h3>Step 3: Configure Your Complaint Form Settings</h3>\n<p>To begin, go to <strong>Settings </strong><strong>» </strong><strong>General.</strong></p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-422696\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/complaint-form-general-settings.jpg\" alt=\"complaint-form-general-settings\" width=\"562\" height=\"464\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/complaint-form-general-settings.jpg 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/complaint-form-general-settings-300x248.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>In this area, you can configure the following:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Form Name.</strong> Rename your form.</li>\n<li><strong>Form Description.</strong> Give your form a description with details about it.</li>\n<li><strong>Submit Button Text.</strong> Customize the text shown on the submit button.</li>\n<li><strong>Spam Prevention.</strong> <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-build-spam-free-wordpress-contact-forms-the-ultimate-guide/\">Enable the anti-spam honeypot feature</a> to prevent spam complaint form submissions and <a href=\"https://www.wpbeginner.com/wordpress-security/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">keep your website secure</a>. You can use this default feature alongside other types of spam prevention such as recaptcha.</li>\n<li><strong>GDPR Enhancement.</strong> You can disable the storing of entry information and user details, such as IP addresses and user agents, in an effort to <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-create-gdpr-compliant-forms/\">comply with GDPR requirements</a>.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Click <strong>Save</strong>.</p>\n<h3>Step 4: Configure Your Complaint Form Notifications</h3>\n<p>Notifications are an excellent way to known when someone submits an entry to your complaint form.</p>\n<p>To get an email when someone completes your WordPress complaint form, you’ll need to <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/setup-form-notification-wpforms/\">set up form notifications in WordPress</a>. Unless you disable the notification feature, you’ll get an email notification whenever someone submits a complaint on your site.</p>\n<p>You can also send multiple notifications when someone completes your complaint form. For example, you can send a notification to yourself and anyone else on your team that might need access to the information submitted in the complaint form.</p>\n<p>Also, if you use <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-use-smart-tags-in-wpforms/\">smart tags</a>, you can send a notification to your site visitors once they finish your complaint form to let them know you received it.</p>\n<p>You can add important information to this email notification if you’d like. For instance, you can mention when people can expect a follow-up to their complaint.</p>\n<p>For help with this, check out our step by step guide on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-multiple-form-notifications-in-wordpress-forms/\">how to send multiple form notifications in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>Also, you have the option to easily brand your notification emails by adding your logo or any image you choose in the custom header image area. The logo/image you choose will show up at the top of email notifications.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-422699\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Custom-Email-Header.jpg\" alt=\"Custom-Email-Header\" width=\"562\" height=\"314\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Custom-Email-Header.jpg 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Custom-Email-Header-300x168.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>This example has a grey background, but you can change the color to something else if you want. These personalized tweaks can make your email notifications look more professional and give them a personal touch. Check out our guide on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-add-custom-header-image-in-your-wpforms-email-template/\">adding a custom header to your email template</a>.</p>\n<h3>Step 5: Configure Your Complaint Form Confirmations</h3>\n<p>Form confirmations are ways to take action immediately after your audience has submitted information to your complaint form. For help with this step, check out our tutorial on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/setup-form-confirmation-wpforms/\">how to setup form confirmations</a>.</p>\n<p>There are 3 different types of confirmations in WPForms:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Message.</strong> This is the default confirmation type that appears after someone hits submit on your form, and it’s customizable. Check out our tips on ways to <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/form-success-message-ideas-to-boost-customer-happiness/\">customize your confirmation message to boost your site visitors&#8217; happiness</a>.</li>\n<li><strong>Display Page.</strong> Automatically send users to any page on your site.</li>\n<li><strong>Redirect.</strong> Useful if you want to take the user to a different website or specialized URL for more complex development.</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>Step 6: Add Your Complaint Form to Your Website</h3>\n<p>After you’ve created your complaint form and changed all the settings to your liking, you need to add your complaint form to your website.</p>\n<p>WPForms lets you add your forms to multiple locations on your site, including your pages, blog posts, and even <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-add-a-contact-form-in-wordpress-sidebar-widget/\">sidebar widgets</a>.</p>\n<p>Let’s take a look at the most common placement option: page/post embedding.</p>\n<p>To begin, create a new page or post in WordPress. Then, click inside the first block (the blank area below your page title) and click on the <strong>Add WPForms</strong> icon.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-422707\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/add-complaint-form-to-new-page.jpg\" alt=\"add-complaint-form-to-new-page\" width=\"562\" height=\"388\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/add-complaint-form-to-new-page.jpg 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/add-complaint-form-to-new-page-300x207.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>The handy WPForms widget will appear inside of your block. Click on the WPForms dropdown that appears and pick which one of the forms you have already created that you want to insert into your page. Select your complaint form.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-429439\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/submit-a-complaint-form-wpforms-dropdown.jpg\" alt=\"submit-a-complaint-form-wpforms-dropdown\" width=\"562\" height=\"427\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/submit-a-complaint-form-wpforms-dropdown.jpg 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/submit-a-complaint-form-wpforms-dropdown-300x228.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Next, publish your page or post so your form will appear on your website.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-422705\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/publish-complaint-form-on-new-page.jpg\" alt=\"publish-complaint-form-on-new-page\" width=\"562\" height=\"412\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/publish-complaint-form-on-new-page.jpg 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/publish-complaint-form-on-new-page-300x220.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>That’s it! You now know how to create a complaint form in WordPress.</p>\n<p>If you find you’re not receiving email notifications, you should check out our guide on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/send-emails-wordpress-using-smtp-step-step/\">how to send emails in WordPress using SMTP.</a></p>\n<p>So, what are you waiting for? Get started with the most powerful <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/\">WordPress forms plugin</a> today.</p>\n<p>And don’t forget, if you like this article, then please follow us on <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/wpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Facebook</a> and <a href=\"http://twitter.com/easywpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Twitter</a>.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-complaint-form-in-wordpress-step-by-step/\">How to Create a Complaint Form in WordPress (Step by Step)</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:82:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-complaint-form-in-wordpress-step-by-step/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"3\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:4;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:42:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:84:\"WPForms Turns 3 Years Old – Bonus Prizes + What’s New &amp; What’s Coming Next\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:36:\"https://wpforms.com/wpforms-turns-3/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:45:\"https://wpforms.com/wpforms-turns-3/#comments\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Thu, 28 Mar 2019 08:08:42 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:12:\"Announcement\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:29:\"https://wpforms.com/?p=427820\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:555:\"<p>WPForms is officially three years old, and wow what an incredible journey it has been. This past year, we accomplished A LOT, thanks to the hard work of our team and continuous support from our users like you. I want to take a few minutes to do a quick recap of all the things that [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/wpforms-turns-3/\">WPForms Turns 3 Years Old &#8211; Bonus Prizes + What&#8217;s New &#038; What&#8217;s Coming Next</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:11:\"Syed Balkhi\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:14048:\"<p>WPForms is officially three years old, and wow what an incredible journey it has been.</p>\n<p>This past year, we accomplished A LOT, thanks to the hard work of our team and continuous support from our users like you.</p>\n<p>I want to take a few minutes to do a quick recap of all the things that happened this past year, share what&#8217;s coming next, and celebrate with a huge giveaway!</p>\n<h3>Fun Third-Year Stats for WPForms</h3>\n<p>WPForms has come a long way in the past 12 months. Here are some fun stats to celebrate our third year.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>WPForms is now the <strong>19th most popular WordPress plugin</strong> of all time with over 1,000,000 active installs (<strong>Update:</strong> We&#8217;ve now passed 2 million active installs mark).</li>\n<li>We have continued to maintain a <strong>4.9 out of 5 star</strong> rating average with over <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/user-reviews/\" title=\"WPForms User Reviews\">3600+ five-star ratings</a>.</li>\n<li>We officially translated WPForms into 4 new languages (German, Spanish, Italian, and Japanese). More translations are coming as we continue our global expansion.</li>\n<li>We added over <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/blog/\" title=\"WPForms Blog\">90+ new blog posts</a> and <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/\" title=\"WPForms Documentation\">64+ new documentation</a> to help you succeed with WPForms.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Although it&#8217;s not a stat, but we now have brand swag (shirt + stickers), and yes you can get one for free.</p>\n<h3>WPForms Birthday Giveaway</h3>\n<p>We want to send this awesome WPForms T-Shirt + Stickers to the first 150 users who share their WPForms story.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpformstshirt.png\" alt=\"WPForms T-Shirt + Stickers\" width=\"620\" height=\"617\" class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-427881\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpformstshirt.png 620w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpformstshirt-150x150.png 150w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpformstshirt-300x300.png 300w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpformstshirt-100x100.png 100w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>All you have to do is share your WPForms story in a quick video and then leave us a comment on this blog post sharing your favorite WPForms feature. </p>\n<p>Don&#8217;t worry, you don&#8217;t need a fancy camera equipment to record a video testimonial. We just want to hear your story and better connect with you.</p>\n<p>That&#8217;s why we have made it super easy to record and upload your video testimonial.</p>\n<p><strong>Method 1. Use your laptop camera to record your video</strong></p>\n<p>Simply open the link below, and you will be able to use your laptop camera to record and upload your video testimonial.</p>\n<p><a class=\"btn btn-block\" style=\"background-color: #659a17 !important; color: #fff !important; padding: 20px 25px !important; text-align: center; text-decoration: none; border-radius: 4px !important; -moz-border-radius: 4px !important; -webkit-border-radius: 4px !important; line-height: 48px; font-weight: bold;\" title=\"Click here to join our affiliate program\" href=\"https://secure.boast.io/site/kudos/WPFORMS\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Click here to Share Your WPForms Story</a></p>\n<p><strong>Method 2. Use your Smart Phone to record a short video</strong></p>\n<p>We&#8217;re using Boast.io to collect video testimonials. You can download the Boast app on your <a href=\"https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/boast.io/id860833000\" title=\"Boast App for iPhone\" rel=\"noopener nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">iPhone</a> or <a href=\"https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=io.boast\" title=\"Boast Google Play App\" rel=\"noopener nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Android Phone</a>, and then type the campaign code: <strong>WPFORMS</strong> to record a video testimonial straight from your phone.</p>\n<p>Remember, don&#8217;t worry about making it professional. We just want to hear your story, what you like about WPForms, and how has WPForms helped you grow your business.</p>\n<p>I look forward to watching your stories and better connecting with you.</p>\n<h3>What&#8217;s New in WPForms</h3>\n<p>We added a lot of powerful features over the last 12 months. Below are some of my favorite:</p>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/conversational-forms-addon/\" title=\"Conversational Forms by WPForms\">Conversational Forms</a></strong></p>\n<p><img src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/interactive-conversational-forms-example.gif\" alt=\"interactive conversational forms example\" width=\"1030\" height=\"742\" class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-391720\" /></p>\n<p>Conversational Forms is the first true interactive form layout built exclusively for WordPress that is guaranteed to boost form completion and your overall form conversions (<a href=\"https://wpforms.com/conversational-forms-demo/\" title=\"Conversational Forms Demo\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">See Demo</a>).</p>\n<p>Conversational Forms help make your WordPress forms feel more human. Instead of asking all twenty questions at once, Conversational Forms takes the one question at a time approach similar to a face-to-face conversation.</p>\n<p>The full-page conversational form layout makes your form less overwhelming and more personal, leading to a better form completion rate.</p>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/form-pages-addon/\" title=\"Form Landing Pages by WPForms\">Form Landing Pages</a></strong></p>\n<p><img src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/wpformsformpagesaddon-1.png\" alt=\"Form Pages by WPForms\" width=\"620\" height=\"300\" class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-366613\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/wpformsformpagesaddon-1.png 620w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/wpformsformpagesaddon-1-300x145.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Form Pages addon for WPForms is the first &#8220;distraction free&#8221; form landing page solution for WordPress (<a href=\"https://wpforms.com/form-pages-demo/\" title=\"Form Pages Demo\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">see demo</a>).</p>\n<p>It allows you to quickly create a dedicated form landing page without hiring a developer or writing any code in literally less than 5 minutes.</p>\n<p>Our distraction-free layout is designed to help you improve your overall form conversions!</p>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/form-locker-addon/\" title=\"Form Permissions for WPForms\">Form Locker for Permissions &#038; Access Control</a></strong></p>\n<p><img src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/form-locker-settings.png\" alt=\"form locker settings\" width=\"562\" height=\"359\" class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-370824\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/form-locker-settings.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/form-locker-settings-300x192.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>WPForms Form Locker addon allows you to lock your WordPress forms with various permissions and access control rules, so you can control who can fill out forms on your website.</p>\n<p>This includes: password protected forms, restrict forms to members only, limit the number of total submissions, limit one entry per person, and close form submissions after specific date / time.</p>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/introducing-wpforms-1-5-0-dashboard-widget-dynamic-field-population-wpforms-challenge-and-more/\" title=\"WPForms Challenge and Dashboard Widget\">WPForms Challenge + Dashboard Widget</a></strong></p>\n<p><img src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/more-steps-in-wpforms-challenge.png\" alt=\"more steps in wpforms challenge\" width=\"562\" height=\"411\" class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-328672\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/more-steps-in-wpforms-challenge.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/more-steps-in-wpforms-challenge-300x219.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>To stay true to our mission, make smart WordPress forms easy, we created an internal challenge called the &#8220;WPForms challenge&#8221; which basically said users should be able to create a simple form and start collecting entries in less than 5 minutes. </p>\n<p>Every time we added a new feature, it was my goal to stress-test the user workflow and make sure that we always stay true to our mission.</p>\n<p>We made this challenge public in form of a guided wizard inside WPForms to not only help new users experience the WPForms difference, but so that every user can give us feedback and hold us accountable.</p>\n<p>As part of this release, we also added a Dashboard widget to give you a quick overview of your form&#8217;s performance.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/wpforms-dashboard-widget-1.png\" alt=\"WPForms Dashboard Widget\" width=\"620\" height=\"452\" class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-330711\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/wpforms-dashboard-widget-1.png 620w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/wpforms-dashboard-widget-1-300x219.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/new-stripe-recurring-functionality-for-your-payment-forms/\" title=\"Stripe Recurring Payments\">Stripe Recurring Payments</a> + <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/announcing-wpforms-1-5-1-form-builder-education-translations-and-payment-checkboxes/\" title=\"Payment Checkboxes\">Payment Checkboxes</a></strong></p>\n<p>One of the most requested features last year was Stripe recurring payments, and of course we listened to our users. We updated our Stripe addon to offer recurring payments ability.</p>\n<p>In a later update, we also added another highly requested feature: Payment Checkboxes, so you can create <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-simple-order-form-in-wordpress/\" title=\"How to Create a Simple Order Form in WordPress (Step by Step)\">simple order forms</a> within just clicks.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/payment-checkboxes.gif\" alt=\"payment checkboxes\" width=\"586\" height=\"282\" class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-367410\" /></p>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/announcing-the-wpforms-gutenberg-block-conditional-form-confirmations-and-more/\" title=\"Conditional Form Confirmations\">Conditional Form Confirmations</a></strong></p>\n<p>One of the most loved features in WPForms is our smart conditional logic. We expanded this feature last year, so you can also use it with your form notification and form confirmations.</p>\n<p>This lets you decide which form confirmation message people after they submit the form based on what they filled out in the form. </p>\n<p>It also lets you create smart form notifications and route the message internally to the right person or team in your organization.</p>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/introducing-new-gdpr-enhancements-for-your-wordpress-forms/\" title=\"GDPR for WPForms\">GDPR Enhancements for WPForms</a></strong></p>\n<p><img src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/gdprenhancements.png\" alt=\"GDPR Enhancements for WPForms\" width=\"620\" height=\"300\" class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-199071\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/gdprenhancements.png 620w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/gdprenhancements-300x145.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>Last year simply cannot be summarized without mentioning GDPR. To help users stay compliant, we added GDPR enhancement features in WPForms for both our Pro and Lite users.</p>\n<p>This included GDPR form field, the ability to disable user cookies, the ability to disable storing of IP addresses, and more.</p>\n<h3>What&#8217;s Coming Next</h3>\n<p>I am truly inspired and proud of what the WPForms team has accomplished in the last 12 months, but there is a lot more to come. We’re working on several new features that you’ve been asking for. Here’s a quick preview of what’s coming next:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Improved Entry Export &#8211; this update will focus on many requested features related to exporting.</li>\n<li>New Language Translations &#8211; we&#8217;re planning to translate WPForms into Portuguese and French.</li>\n<li>AJAX Form Submit &#8211; this is another frequently requested feature. It will allow users to submit forms without reloading the page which will make it easy to embed your forms in apps like <a href=\"https://optinmonster.com/\" title=\"OptinMonster\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">OptinMonster</a> and others.</li>\n<li>WP Mail SMTP Pro &#8211; we acquired <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/wp-mail-smtp/\" title=\"WP Mail SMTP\" rel=\"noopener nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">WP Mail SMTP plugin</a> to help fix the WordPress email deliverability issues. While the free version is great, we&#8217;re launching a Pro version to add more powerful features and offer proper SMTP setup service.</li>\n<li>and of course a whole lot more &#8230;</li>\n</ul>\n<p>We&#8217;re always listening to user feedback for new feature ideas and improvements. If you ever have an idea for a new addon or feature that you&#8217;d like to see, please <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/contact/\" title=\"Send us your feature ideas for WPForms\">get in touch</a>.</p>\n<p>Thank you for your continued support in making WPForms the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/\" title=\"WPForms is the best WordPress Contact Form Plugin\">best WordPress contact form plugin</a>.</p>\n<p><em>Syed and the WPForms Team</em></p>\n<p>P.S. Don&#8217;t have a WPForms Pro license? <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/pricing/\" title=\"Get Started with WPForms Pro\">Click here to get started today</a>, and experience the WPForms difference.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/wpforms-turns-3/\">WPForms Turns 3 Years Old &#8211; Bonus Prizes + What&#8217;s New &#038; What&#8217;s Coming Next</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:41:\"https://wpforms.com/wpforms-turns-3/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:2:\"10\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:5;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:42:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:66:\"[Case Study] 6 Ways WPBeginner Uses WPForms to Grow Their Business\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:71:\"https://wpforms.com/how-wpbeginner-uses-wpforms-to-grow-their-business/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:79:\"https://wpforms.com/how-wpbeginner-uses-wpforms-to-grow-their-business/#respond\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Mon, 25 Mar 2019 15:01:17 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"Marketing\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:29:\"https://wpforms.com/?p=425055\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:591:\"<p>Aside from making smart forms easy, one of the things that make WPForms the best drag &#038; drop WordPress form builder is our focus on empowering business owners to grow their business. Every feature that we build is results driven. In this case study, I will share how WPBeginner is using WPForms to grow their [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-wpbeginner-uses-wpforms-to-grow-their-business/\">[Case Study] 6 Ways WPBeginner Uses WPForms to Grow Their Business</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:11:\"Syed Balkhi\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:10933:\"<p>Aside from making smart forms easy, one of the things that make WPForms the best drag &#038; drop WordPress form builder is our focus on empowering business owners to grow their business.</p>\n<p>Every feature that we build is results driven. In this case study, I will share how WPBeginner is using WPForms to grow their blog traffic and revenue.</p>\n<h3>Meet WPBeginner</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.wpbeginner.com/\" title=\"WPBeginner\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">WPBeginner</a> is the largest free WordPress resource site for beginners. </p>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.wpbeginner.com/\" title=\"WPBeginner\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpbeginner-screenshot.png\" alt=\"WPBeginner Screenshot\" width=\"620\" height=\"450\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-425140\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpbeginner-screenshot.png 620w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpbeginner-screenshot-300x218.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></a></p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> I&#8217;m also the founder of WPBeginner, and I had our team build WPForms, so we can have more business focused form features that were lacking in other WordPress plugins.</p>\n<p>Here are 6 ways we&#8217;re using WPForms on WPBeginner to increase our blog traffic and revenue.</p>\n<h3>1. Contact Form</h3>\n<p>Every website needs a contact form. It allows your website visitors an easy way to get in touch with you. </p>\n<p>Since WPBeginner get millions of visitors every month, it&#8217;s important for us to have a contact form that&#8217;s not only reliable, but has a way to block spam.</p>\n<p>WPForms comes with three built-in spam protection solutions: invisible honeypot, Google reCAPTCHA, and <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/custom-catpcha-addon/\" title=\"Custom Questions CAPTCHA for WordPress\">custom questions CAPTCHA</a>.</p>\n<p>WPBeginner website uses the combination of invisible honeypot and Google reCAPTCHA which blocks out all spam.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpbeginnercontactform.png\" alt=\"WPBeginner Contact Form\" width=\"620\" height=\"599\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-425142\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpbeginnercontactform.png 620w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpbeginnercontactform-300x290.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p><strong>Pro Tip:</strong> <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/setup-captcha-wpforms/\" title=\"How to Set Up reCAPTCHA in WPForms\">Setup reCAPTCHA on your WordPress forms</a> to reduce spam form submissions.</p>\n<h3>2. Grow Email List</h3>\n<p>Every industry expert knows that more than 70% of people leaving your website will never return. </p>\n<p>At WPBeginner, it&#8217;s important for us to convert as many website visitors into email subscribers, so we can continue to grow our website traffic and revenue.</p>\n<p>WPForms comes with built-in email marketing integrations for <a title=\"Constant Contact\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/refer/constant-contact/\" rel=\"nofollow nooperner\" target=\"_blank\">Constant Contact</a>, <a title=\"MailChimp\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/refer/mailchimp/\" rel=\"nofollow nooperner\" target=\"_blank\">MailChimp</a>, <a title=\"Drip\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/refer/drip/\" rel=\"nofollow nooperner\" target=\"_blank\">Drip</a>, <a  title=\"GetResponse\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/refer/getresponse-2/\" rel=\"nofollow nooperner\" target=\"_blank\" >GetResponse</a>, Campaign Monitor, and over 1000+ others through <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/zapier-addon/\" title=\"Zapier Addon\">Zapier</a>.</p>\n<p>WPBeginner website uses WPForms native email marketing integration combined with smart conditional logic to turn all of our contact forms into newsletter signup forms.</p>\n<p>In each form, we add a checkbox field that asks users if they want to receive weekly WordPress tutorials and updates from WPBeginner. </p>\n<p><img src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpbeginner-contact-form-optin.png\" alt=\"WPBeginner Contact Form Optin\" width=\"620\" height=\"568\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-425172\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpbeginner-contact-form-optin.png 620w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpbeginner-contact-form-optin-300x275.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>We use the conditional logic feature of WPForms to automatically subscribe any user who checks the box to our weekly email newsletter.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpforms-conditional-newsletter-signup.png\" alt=\"WPForms Conditional Newsletter Signup Form\" width=\"620\" height=\"390\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-425170\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpforms-conditional-newsletter-signup.png 620w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpforms-conditional-newsletter-signup-300x189.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<h3>3. Reduce Form Abandonment</h3>\n<p>Form abandonment is a real problem. </p>\n<p>WPBeginner uses the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/form-abandonment-addon/\" title=\"Form Abandonment Addon for WPForms\">form abandonment</a> feature of WPForms to capture partial form submissions on our important business inquiry forms. This helps the team close more partnership deals.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/WPForms-Form-Abandonment-addon-settings.png\" alt=\"WPForms Form Abandonment addon settings\" width=\"468\" height=\"282\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-192194\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/WPForms-Form-Abandonment-addon-settings.png 468w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/WPForms-Form-Abandonment-addon-settings-300x181.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 468px) 100vw, 468px\" /></p>\n<p>Although it&#8217;s not live yet, WPBeginner team is also planning to use WPForms&#8217; distraction-free <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/form-pages-addon/\" title=\"Form Landing Pages for WordPress by WPForms\">form landing pages</a> to reduce form abandonment on some of their lead forms.</p>\n<h3>4. Reader Surveys</h3>\n<p>WPBeginner team regularly conducts reader surveys to gather feedback and make data-driven decisions to grow the website.</p>\n<p>They use WPForms&#8217; powerful <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/surveys-and-polls-addon/\" title=\"Surveys and Polls by WPForms\">survey and polls addon</a> to create smart survey forms, so they can get real-time insights from WPForms interactive survey reports. </p>\n<p><img src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/Graph-option-in-WPForms-survey-report.gif\" alt=\"Graph option in WPForms survey report\" width=\"756\" height=\"566\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-148990\" /></p>\n<p>Since some of the surveys require more granular permissions &#038; access control, WPBeginner team uses the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/form-locker-addon/\" title=\"Form Locker Addon\">form locker addon</a> by WPForms to limit the number of total submissions, password-protect forms, and automatically closing submissions after specific date.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/form-locker-settings.png\" alt=\"form locker settings\" width=\"562\" height=\"359\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-370824\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/form-locker-settings.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/form-locker-settings-300x192.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>In the future, they are planning to use WPForms brand new <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/conversational-forms-addon/\" title=\"Conversational Forms Addon\">conversational forms addon</a> to improve form completion rate.</p>\n<p><a class=\"btn btn-block\" style=\"background-color: #659a17 !important; color: #fff !important; padding: 20px 25px !important; text-align: center; text-decoration: none; border-radius: 4px !important; -moz-border-radius: 4px !important; -webkit-border-radius: 4px !important; line-height: 48px; font-weight: bold;\" title=\"Click here to join our affiliate program\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/conversational-forms-demo/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Click here to see Conversational Form Demo</a></p>\n<h3>5. Get New Blog Post Ideas</h3>\n<p>Aside from reader surveys, WPBeginner also has a <a href=\"https://www.wpbeginner.com/make-a-suggestion/\" title=\"Make a Suggestion to WPBeginner\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">Make a Suggestion page</a> where users can submit blog post ideas.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpbeginner-make-a-suggestion.png\" alt=\"WPBeginner Make a Suggestion Form\" width=\"620\" height=\"504\" class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-425205\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpbeginner-make-a-suggestion.png 620w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/wpbeginner-make-a-suggestion-300x244.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>WPBeginner team uses the responses from this form to plan their blog calendar.</p>\n<p>If you&#8217;re a blogger or even a regular business, you should definitely consider creating a Make a Suggestion page. You will be surprised how many great ideas will come from it.</p>\n<h3>6. Collect Payments</h3>\n<p>WPForms allows you to create <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-simple-order-form-in-wordpress/\" title=\"How to Create a Simple Order Form in WordPress (Step by Step)\">simple order forms</a> to accept payments right on your WordPress site.</p>\n<p>WPBeginner team uses WPForms to create simple payment forms that makes it easy for users to purchase support services. </p>\n<p>Although this is not a big chunk of revenue for WPBeginner since they do their best to offer free support, on rare occasions they may ask for a payment to solve a more complicated WordPress problem for a reader.</p>\n<h3>Final Thoughts</h3>\n<p>WPForms plays a very important role in growing WPBeginner traffic and revenue. Even though WPBeginner team does not use all of WPForms powerful features, they&#8217;re using several important features to streamline their workflow and grow the overall business.</p>\n<p>How are you using WPForms on your website? Leave a comment and let us know.</p>\n<p>Want to see all the powerful features that are available at WPForms? <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/features/\" title=\"WPForms Features\">Click here to see all WPForms features</a>. </p>\n<p>Not using WPForms on your site yet? Click here to <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/pricing/\" title=\"https://wpforms.com/pricing/\">get started with WPForms Pro</a>. </p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-wpbeginner-uses-wpforms-to-grow-their-business/\">[Case Study] 6 Ways WPBeginner Uses WPForms to Grow Their Business</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:76:\"https://wpforms.com/how-wpbeginner-uses-wpforms-to-grow-their-business/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:6;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:51:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:72:\"How to Securely Send WordPress Emails Using Gmail SMTP with WP Mail SMTP\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:75:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-securely-send-wordpress-emails-using-gmail-smtp/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:84:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-securely-send-wordpress-emails-using-gmail-smtp/#comments\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Fri, 22 Mar 2019 17:35:31 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:4:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:19:\"WordPress Tutorials\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:4:\"smtp\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:17:\"form notification\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:13:\"notifications\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:28:\"https://wpforms.com/?p=35577\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:611:\"<p>Looking for a secure SMTP plugin that helps you receive email notifications from your WordPress contact forms? With WP Mail SMTP, you can fix delivery issues by authenticating emails through your Gmail or G Suite account &#8212; all while keeping your login credentials safe. In this post, we’ll show you how to set up WP [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-securely-send-wordpress-emails-using-gmail-smtp/\">How to Securely Send WordPress Emails Using Gmail SMTP with WP Mail SMTP</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:13:\"Shahzad Saeed\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:25533:\"<p>Looking for a secure SMTP plugin that helps you receive email notifications from your WordPress contact forms? With WP Mail SMTP, you can fix delivery issues by authenticating emails through your Gmail or G Suite account &#8212; all while keeping your login credentials safe. </p>\n<p>In this post, we’ll show you how to set up WP Mail SMTP for sending WordPress emails with your Gmail or G Suite email address.</p>\n<h3>Why You’re Not Receiving Notifications</h3>\n<p>By default, WordPress uses the <a href=\"http://www.wpbeginner.com/glossary/php/\" target=\"_blank\">PHP</a> mail function to send emails generated by WordPress or any contact plugin like <a href=\"http://wpforms.com/\">WPForms</a>.  The most common reason for not getting emails is that your WordPress hosting server is not configured to use PHP mail function.</p>\n<p>In addition to this, anti-spam efforts by email providers can impact your emails as well. As part of their filtering process, many email providers will check whether your email originates from the same domain noted in the From Email. For example, if your email claims to be sent from your Gmail address but is actually sent from your website&#8217;s server (rather than Gmail&#8217;s server), your email may be sent to spam or not be delivered at all.</p>\n<p>You can fix this by using SMTP instead of the PHP mail function. SMTP (Simple Mail Transfer Protocol) is the industry standard for sending emails reliably.</p>\n<h3>Why Use the WP Mail SMTP Plugin?</h3>\n<p>The main benefit of using the WP Mail SMTP plugin is that it lets you send WordPress emails securely using your Gmail or G Suite account without requiring to enable less secure apps in your account.</p>\n<p>In addition, unlike many other SMTP options, you won’t need to enter your Gmail username and password in your WordPress dashboard where other site users can see them. By using this method, you&#8217;ll help to <a href=\"http://www.wpbeginner.com/wordpress-security/\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Ultimate Guide to WordPress Security\">keep your WordPress site secure</a>.</p>\n<p>Let’s take a look at how to set up WP Mail SMTP for sending WordPress emails.</p>\n<h3>Step 1: Install the WP Mail SMTP Plugin</h3>\n<p>The first thing you need to do is to install and activate the <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/wp-mail-smtp/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">WP Mail SMTP</a> plugin. For step-by-step instructions, you can check out <a href=\"http://www.wpbeginner.com/beginners-guide/step-by-step-guide-to-install-a-wordpress-plugin-for-beginners/\" target=\"_blank\">WPBeginner&#8217;s guide on how to install a WordPress plugin</a>.</p>\n<p>After installing and activating WP Mail SMTP, go to <strong>Settings » WP Mail SMTP</strong> to open the plugin settings page. </p>\n<p><img src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Open-WP-Mail-SMTP-settings-page-1.png\" alt=\"Open WP Mail SMTP settings page\" width=\"450\" height=\"309\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-423553\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Open-WP-Mail-SMTP-settings-page-1.png 450w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Open-WP-Mail-SMTP-settings-page-1-300x206.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 450px) 100vw, 450px\" /></p>\n<p>At the top of this page, you&#8217;ll see the <strong>From Email</strong> and <strong>From Name</strong>. You can ignore these settings, because Google will automatically force these values to match the email account used in the next step.</p>\n<p>To start the setup process, you&#8217;ll need to scroll to the <strong>Mailer</strong> field and select the <strong>Google</strong> option.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Select-Google-mailer-option-in-WP-Mail-SMTP-1.png\" alt=\"Select Google mailer option in WP Mail SMTP\" width=\"562\" height=\"214\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-423571\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Select-Google-mailer-option-in-WP-Mail-SMTP-1.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Select-Google-mailer-option-in-WP-Mail-SMTP-1-300x114.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<div class=\"alert alert-warning\"><strong>Note:</strong> Google&#8217;s API (used by the Google mailer) will not allow you to customize certain aspects of your emails, such as the Reply To email address. If this is an important option in your project, please consider using <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-fix-wordpress-contact-form-not-sending-email-with-smtp/\" title=\"How to Fix WordPress Contact Form Not Sending Email With SMTP\">an alternative mailer option</a>.</div>\n<p>You can skip the <strong>Return Path</strong> checkbox, as Google does not allow this setting to be altered.</p>\n<p>Next, you should see a new Gmail section appear. Here, you&#8217;ll see fields for <strong>Client Secret</strong> and <strong>Client ID</strong>.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Gmail-section-of-WP-Mail-SMTP-settings.png\" alt=\"Gmail section of WP Mail SMTP settings\" width=\"562\" height=\"359\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-423589\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Gmail-section-of-WP-Mail-SMTP-settings.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Gmail-section-of-WP-Mail-SMTP-settings-300x192.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>To get the information for these fields, you&#8217;ll need to create a web application through your Google account. This doesn&#8217;t require any coding, and we&#8217;ll show you exactly what to do.</p>\n<h3>Step 2: Create a Web Application</h3>\n<p>To create an application, you&#8217;ll first need to <a href=\"https://console.developers.google.com/flows/enableapi?apiid=gmail&#038;pli=1\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">sign into your Gmail account and access Gmail&#8217;s application registration</a>. Clicking that link should open this Google page in a new tab or window, and you&#8217;ll want to keep your site settings open (we&#8217;ll return to those later).</p>\n<p>Once you&#8217;ve followed that link and logged into your Gmail account, you should see a form named &#8220;Register your application for Gmail API in Google API Console&#8221;. </p>\n<p>In the dropdown labeled <strong>Select a project where your application will be registered</strong>, leave the default option of <strong>Create a project</strong>. In some cases, you may also be asked to agree to terms of service.</p>\n<p>After filling out this form, go ahead and click the <strong>Continue</strong> button.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Create-a-new-project-for-Google-application.jpg\" alt=\"Create a new project for Google application\" width=\"562\" height=\"323\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-423633\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Create-a-new-project-for-Google-application.jpg 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Create-a-new-project-for-Google-application-300x172.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Next, you should see a screen that says &#8220;The API is enabled&#8221;. To proceed to the setup page, click the <strong>Go to credentials</strong> button.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Gmail-API-is-enabled.png\" alt=\"Gmail API is enabled\" width=\"500\" height=\"205\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-423593\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Gmail-API-is-enabled.png 500w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Gmail-API-is-enabled-300x123.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 500px) 100vw, 500px\" /></p>\n<p>In the next page, you’ll be prompted to determine the credentials you need. Here are the fields on this page and the options you&#8217;ll need to select:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Which API are you using?</strong> Gmail API</li>\n<li><strong>Where will you be calling the API from?</strong> Web server (e.g. node.js, Tomcat)</li>\n<li><strong>What data will you be accessing?</strong> User data</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Once you&#8217;ve made these selections, click the <strong>What credentials do I need?</strong> button to go to the next step.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Add-credentials-to-Gmail-app-project.png\" alt=\"Add credentials to Gmail app project\" width=\"500\" height=\"513\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-423600\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Add-credentials-to-Gmail-app-project.png 500w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Add-credentials-to-Gmail-app-project-292x300.png 292w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 500px) 100vw, 500px\" /></p>\n<p>After clicking this button, Google will show a popup asking you to set up a consent screen. Go ahead and click on the <strong>Set Up Consent Screen Option</strong>. </p>\n<p><img src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Open-OAuth-consent-screen.png\" alt=\"Open OAuth consent screen\" width=\"562\" height=\"279\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-422938\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Open-OAuth-consent-screen.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Open-OAuth-consent-screen-300x149.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>This will open a new tab or window. Be sure to keep the original tab/window open, as we&#8217;ll return to it a little later.</p>\n<p>In the new tab/window, you&#8217;ll be asked for several details to prepare your consent screen. This is the permissions screen that will display to you later in the setup process (never seen by your users).</p>\n<p>If you have a G Suite account, you&#8217;ll first set <strong>Application type</strong> to <strong>Internal</strong>. You will not see this option if you&#8217;re using an @gmail.com email account.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Select-internal-application-type.jpg\" alt=\"Select internal application type\" width=\"562\" height=\"381\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-423628\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Select-internal-application-type.jpg 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Select-internal-application-type-300x203.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>For <strong>Application name,</strong> you can add the name of your website (or any other name that feels logical to you).</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Fill-in-app-details.png\" alt=\"Fill in app details\" width=\"562\" height=\"365\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-422941\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Fill-in-app-details.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Fill-in-app-details-300x195.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Then, you can skip down to <strong>Authorized domains</strong> and add the URL for your website. Be sure to not include <code>http://</code> or <code>https://</code> here.</p>\n<p>For <strong>Application Homepage link</strong>, <strong>Application Privacy Policy link</strong>, and <strong>Application Terms of Service link</strong>, you can again just add your website URL. You don&#8217;t need to have special privacy or terms pages in place for this app, as again this consent screen will only ever be seen by you.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Add-authorized-domain-information-to-Google-consent.png\" alt=\"Add authorized domain information to Google consent\" width=\"588\" height=\"562\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-423477\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Add-authorized-domain-information-to-Google-consent.png 588w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Add-authorized-domain-information-to-Google-consent-300x287.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 588px) 100vw, 588px\" /></p>\n<p>When you&#8217;re ready, click the <strong>Save</strong> button at the bottom of this screen.</p>\n<p>After saving your consent screen settings, Google will take you back to an API credentials screen. You can ignore this, and instead return to the first tab/window. </p>\n<p>For this step, you&#8217;ll be creating an OAuth client ID. OAuth, or Open Authorization, is what will provide permission for your website to use your Gmail account to authenticate emails.</p>\n<p>For the <strong>Name</strong> field, enter anything you like or leave the default name. This is only for reference within your Google account.</p>\n<p>For <strong>Authorized JavaScript origins</strong>, you&#8217;ll need to enter your site&#8217;s URL.</p>\n<p>Last, we need to fill out the <strong>Authorized redirect URIs</strong> field. To get the URI for your site, you&#8217;ll need to go back to the tab or window with your WordPress site. Still on the <strong>Settings &raquo; WP Mail SMTP</strong> page, you&#8217;ll need to look under the Gmail section for the field labeled <strong>Authorized redirect URI</strong>.</p>\n<p>The value in this field should be your site&#8217;s URL followed by some extra details. You&#8217;ll need to copy this value, which is easily done by clicking the button with the copy icon. </p>\n<p><img src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Use-button-to-copy-authorized-redirect-URI-from-WP-Mail-SMTP-settings.png\" alt=\"Use button to copy authorized redirect URI from WP Mail SMTP settings\" width=\"562\" height=\"134\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-423641\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Use-button-to-copy-authorized-redirect-URI-from-WP-Mail-SMTP-settings.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Use-button-to-copy-authorized-redirect-URI-from-WP-Mail-SMTP-settings-300x72.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>After copying the URI, return to the Google APIs page and paste it into the field under <strong>Authorized redirect URIs</strong>.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Create-OAuth-client-ID.png\" alt=\"Create OAuth client ID\" width=\"562\" height=\"633\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-423481\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Create-OAuth-client-ID.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Create-OAuth-client-ID-266x300.png 266w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>When you finish filling out these details, you may see a <strong>Refresh</strong> button near the bottom of the page. Go ahead and click this.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Click-Refresh-button.png\" alt=\"Click Refresh button\" width=\"437\" height=\"267\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-423519\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Click-Refresh-button.png 437w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Click-Refresh-button-300x183.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 437px) 100vw, 437px\" /></p>\n<p>Next, you can click the <strong>Create client ID</strong> button.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Click-blue-button-to-create-OAuth-client-ID.png\" alt=\"Click blue button to create OAuth client ID\" width=\"386\" height=\"264\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-423522\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Click-blue-button-to-create-OAuth-client-ID.png 386w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Click-blue-button-to-create-OAuth-client-ID-300x205.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 386px) 100vw, 386px\" /></p>\n<p>You’ve now successfully created a Google web application!</p>\n<p>Now we need to see the full details. On the last screen, click <strong>I’ll do this later</strong> to go to the Credentials page.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Click-Ill-do-this-later.png\" alt=\"Click Ill do this later\" width=\"462\" height=\"496\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-423524\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Click-Ill-do-this-later.png 462w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Click-Ill-do-this-later-279x300.png 279w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 462px) 100vw, 462px\" /></p>\n<h3 id=\"step-3\">Step 3: Grant Permissions and Send Test Email</h3>\n<p>On the Credentials page, you can now see the details of the web application you just created. To view <strong>Client ID</strong> and <strong>Client Secret</strong>, click the pencil icon.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Click-pencil-icon-to-see-details.png\" alt=\"Click pencil icon to see details\" width=\"562\" height=\"100\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-423506\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Click-pencil-icon-to-see-details.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Click-pencil-icon-to-see-details-300x53.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>This will open all of the details for your app. On this page, you&#8217;ll see the <strong>Client ID</strong> and <strong>Client secret</strong> values.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Copy-Client-ID-and-Client-secret.png\" alt=\"Copy Client ID and Client secret\" width=\"562\" height=\"299\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-423510\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Copy-Client-ID-and-Client-secret.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Copy-Client-ID-and-Client-secret-300x160.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Each of these will need to be copied into your WP Mail SMTP settings back in your WordPress admin screen.</p>\n<div class=\"alert alert-warning\"><strong>Note:</strong> Be very careful not to copy any extra text or spaces with your Client ID or Client Secret, as this will result in an error in the next step.</div>\n<p><img src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/Copy-in-Client-ID-and-secret-to-WP-Mail-SMTP-settings.png\" alt=\"Copy in Client ID and secret to WP Mail SMTP settings\" width=\"620\" height=\"243\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-118086\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/Copy-in-Client-ID-and-secret-to-WP-Mail-SMTP-settings.png 620w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/Copy-in-Client-ID-and-secret-to-WP-Mail-SMTP-settings-300x118.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 620px) 100vw, 620px\" /></p>\n<p>After saving these settings, the page will refresh. Before Google allows this information to be used to connect to your account, however, you must grant permission. </p>\n<p>To do this, scroll to the bottom of this page and click the button labeled <strong>Allow plugin to send emails using your Google account</strong>.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Authorize-plugin-to-send-emails-with-Gmail.png\" alt=\"Authorize plugin to send emails with Gmail\" width=\"562\" height=\"178\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-423617\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Authorize-plugin-to-send-emails-with-Gmail.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Authorize-plugin-to-send-emails-with-Gmail-300x95.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>This will open a login screen for Google. Go ahead and log into the account you&#8217;re setting this SMTP up with. Then, you&#8217;ll see a screen asking for permission for this site to send email on your behalf. </p>\n<p>When you&#8217;re ready, click the <strong>Allow</strong> button to proceed.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Provide-permissions-to-your-Google-app.png\" alt=\"Provide permissions to your Google app\" width=\"462\" height=\"574\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-423529\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Provide-permissions-to-your-Google-app.png 462w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Provide-permissions-to-your-Google-app-241x300.png 241w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 462px) 100vw, 462px\" /></p>\n<p>Next, you&#8217;ll be returned to your WP Mail SMTP settings and a success message will be displayed. Now that the connection is complete, you&#8217;re ready to send a test email under the <strong>Email Test</strong> tab.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Gmail-connection-success-with-WP-Mail-SMTP.png\" alt=\"Gmail connection success with WP Mail SMTP\" width=\"562\" height=\"290\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-423625\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Gmail-connection-success-with-WP-Mail-SMTP.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Gmail-connection-success-with-WP-Mail-SMTP-300x155.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Once the Test Email tab is open, you&#8217;ll need to enter a valid email address and click the <strong>Send Email</strong> button. Be sure to use an email address you have access to so you can confirm the email is delivered.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/Send-a-test-email-through-WP-Mail-SMTP.png\" alt=\"Send a test email through WP Mail SMTP\" width=\"430\" height=\"360\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-118145\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/Send-a-test-email-through-WP-Mail-SMTP.png 430w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/Send-a-test-email-through-WP-Mail-SMTP-300x251.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 430px) 100vw, 430px\" /></p>\n<p>When the test message has been sent, you&#8217;ll see a success message at the top of this tab.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/WP-Mail-SMTP-test-email-was-sent-successfully.png\" alt=\"WP Mail SMTP test email was sent successfully\" width=\"292\" height=\"274\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-118113\" /></p>\n<p>You should also soon receive a test email at the email address you entered.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Test-email-for-WP-Mail-SMTP-Gmail.png\" alt=\"Test email for WP Mail SMTP Gmail\" width=\"562\" height=\"431\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-423663\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Test-email-for-WP-Mail-SMTP-Gmail.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Test-email-for-WP-Mail-SMTP-Gmail-300x230.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<h3>Frequently Asked Questions</h3>\n<h6>What If the Test Email Doesn&#8217;t Send Successfully?</h6>\n<p>If the SMTP test email isn&#8217;t able to send, a debug log will appear with additional details. Here are some of the possible error messages and how to resolve them.</p>\n<p><strong>401. That’s an error.<br />\nError: invalid_client</strong><br />\nThis error appears when the Client ID isn&#8217;t able to be read properly. To fix, try copying the Client ID in again and check that there&#8217;s no whitespace or extra text.</p>\n<p><strong>400. That’s an error.<br />\nError: invalid_request<br />\nMissing required parameter: client_id</strong><br />\nThis error will display when the Client ID field is empty or not able to be read properly. To fix, copy in the Client ID again and be careful to not add extra text or whitespace.</p>\n<p><strong>cURL error 60: SSL certificate problem</strong><br />\nThis message means that the server is missing a certificate that’s required for SMTP to work. To fix, you&#8217;ll need to contact your site&#8217;s hosting provider to ask them to install this certificate (most likely the cacert.pem certificate, though it&#8217;s best to ask your host to check).</p>\n<p><strong>“code”: 401,<br />\n“message”: “Login Required”</strong><br />\nIf you see this in the debug message, permission still needs to be granted to your use Google account. For instructions on how to fix this, please see <a href=\"#step-3\" title=\"Step 3: Grant Permissions and Send Test Email\">Step 3</a> of this tutorial. Also, be sure to check that the From Email in your SMTP settings matches the email used to setup the Google app.</p>\n<h6>What If I Want to Switch to A Different Email Later?</h6>\n<p>If you&#8217;d like to change to a different Gmail/G Suite email address, you&#8217;ll need to repeat all tutorial steps above. This includes generating a new Client ID and Client Secret under this other email account.</p>\n<p>When you get to the Authorization step (under Step 3), save your settings and then click the <strong>Remove Connection</strong> button. This will remove the authorization for your original email account and allow you to repeat the authorization steps with the new email.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Remove-connection-in-WP-Mail-SMTP.png\" alt=\"Remove connection in WP Mail SMTP\" width=\"703\" height=\"124\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-223847\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Remove-connection-in-WP-Mail-SMTP.png 703w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Remove-connection-in-WP-Mail-SMTP-300x53.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 703px) 100vw, 703px\" /></p>\n<p>That’s it! You’ve successfully configured WP Mail SMTP&#8217;s Google mailer on your WordPress site.</p>\n<p>What are you waiting for? Get started with the most powerful <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/\">WordPress forms plugin</a> today.</p>\n<p>If you like this article, then please follow us on <a href=\"http://facebook.com/wpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Facebook </a>and <a href=\"http://twitter.com/easywpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Twitter</a> for more free WordPress tutorials.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-securely-send-wordpress-emails-using-gmail-smtp/\">How to Securely Send WordPress Emails Using Gmail SMTP with WP Mail SMTP</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:80:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-securely-send-wordpress-emails-using-gmail-smtp/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:3:\"816\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:7;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:54:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:62:\"How to Create a Video Release Form in WordPress (Step by Step)\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:81:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-video-release-form-in-wordpress-step-by-step/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:89:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-video-release-form-in-wordpress-step-by-step/#respond\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Tue, 05 Mar 2019 13:00:51 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:5:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:19:\"WordPress Tutorials\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:7:\"WPForms\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:15:\"signature addon\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:18:\"video release form\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:4;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:15:\"video marketing\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:29:\"https://wpforms.com/?p=390974\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:593:\"<p>Do you need an easy and efficient way to get people’s consent to use video footage that you’ve taken of them during activities and at events? It’s crucial you have people’s permission to take and use video of them. In this article, we’ll show you how to create a video release form in WordPress. The [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-video-release-form-in-wordpress-step-by-step/\">How to Create a Video Release Form in WordPress (Step by Step)</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:14:\"Lindsay Liedke\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:15135:\"<p>Do you need an easy and efficient way to get people’s consent to use video footage that you’ve taken of them during activities and at events? It’s crucial you have people’s permission to take and use video of them.</p>\n<p>In this article, we’ll show you how to create a video release form in WordPress.</p>\n<h3>The Importance of a Video Release Form</h3>\n<p>If you’re a video producer it’s in your best interest to always have anyone recorded fill out a video production release form so you avoid any liability and have the opportunity to do what you want with the footage.</p>\n<p>Here are some reasons why video release forms are so important:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Anyone that doesn’t fill out a video release form may later ask you to pull their likeness from your video</li>\n<li>If you videotape a minor and don’t have parental consent, you could face legal trouble</li>\n<li>So the signer of the video release form can release their right to approve or disapprove of the finished product</li>\n<li>To give people the impression you are a professional and care about their rights</li>\n<li>To ensure those in your film are not violating another contract they’ve signed, and removing liability from yourself if they are</li>\n<li>Because it’s the nice thing to do, even if you’re in a public place and don’t technically need permission</li>\n</ul>\n<p>If you approach people in a nice, professional way when videotaping at an event or activity, chances are they’ll sign the form without a problem. And if they don’t, and give you a hassle, just be happy you avoided having to deal with them later after you’ve edited your film and they want out of it.</p>\n<p>Let’s take a look at how to create a video release form in WordPress.</p>\n<h3>Step 1: Create a Video Release Form in WordPress</h3>\n<p>Using WPForms is the easiest way to create a standard video release form in WordPress. WPForms comes with the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/form-templates-pack-addon/\">Form Templates Pack addon</a> that allows you to choose from 100+ pre-built templates for every niche and industry, including a video release form template.</p>\n<p>The first thing you’ll need to do is install and activate the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/pricing/\">WPForms plugin</a>. For more details, see this step by step guide on <a title=\"Step by step guide on How to Install a WordPress Plugin\" href=\"http://www.wpbeginner.com/beginners-guide/step-by-step-guide-to-install-a-wordpress-plugin-for-beginners/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">how to install a plugin in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>Next, you’ll need to install and activate the Form Templates Pack addon.</p>\n<p>To do this, go to <strong>WPForms</strong> » <strong>Addon</strong> and find the one labeled <strong>Form Templates Pack addon</strong>.</p>\n<p>Click <strong>Install Addon</strong> and then <strong>Activate</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-291194\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-templates-pack-addon.png\" alt=\"form templates pack addon\" width=\"562\" height=\"193\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-templates-pack-addon.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/form-templates-pack-addon-300x103.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Now you’ll need to create a new form.</p>\n<p>To do this, go to <strong>WPForms</strong> » <strong>Add New</strong>, and name your form. Then, scroll down to the section labeled <strong>Additional Templates</strong> and type “video release” into the search bar.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-390996\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/video-release-form-template.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"562\" height=\"255\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/video-release-form-template.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/video-release-form-template-300x136.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>When the pre-built video release form template loads, most of the work is already done for you.</p>\n<p>You’ll see form fields for the following:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Name of person in the video</li>\n<li>Section Divider with terms and conditions</li>\n<li>Date / Time</li>\n<li>Agreement checkbox</li>\n</ul>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-390994\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/video-release-form.png\" alt=\"video release form\" width=\"562\" height=\"425\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/video-release-form.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/video-release-form-300x227.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>If you want to see the online video release form template in action, head over and check out our <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/demo/video-release-form-demo/\">sample video release form demo</a>.</p>\n<p>You can add additional fields to your form by dragging them from the left hand panel to the right hand panel.</p>\n<p>Then, click on the field to make any changes. You can also click on a form field and drag it to rearrange the order on your Video release form.</p>\n<p>For example, if you want to require a parent or guardian signature on your forms because it’s a video release form for minors, add the <strong>Signature</strong> form field to your video release form template.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-390993\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/signature-form-field-example.png\" alt=\"signature form field example\" width=\"562\" height=\"372\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/signature-form-field-example.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/signature-form-field-example-300x199.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Just make sure to select the <strong>Required</strong> checkbox so parents or guardians can’t submit their form without a signature.</p>\n<p>You might also consider adding Name, Email, or Phone form fields to your video release form template so you can get in touch with people you’ve recorded later for any reason.</p>\n<p>When your video release form looks the way you want it to, click <strong>Save</strong>.</p>\n<h3>Step 2: Configure Your Video Release Form Settings</h3>\n<p>To start, go to <strong>Settings</strong> » <strong>General</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-246850\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/WPForms-General-Settings.png\" alt=\"WPForms General Settings\" width=\"562\" height=\"443\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/WPForms-General-Settings.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/WPForms-General-Settings-300x236.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Here you can configure the following:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Form Name.</strong> Rename your form here.</li>\n<li><strong>Form Description.</strong> Give your form a description.</li>\n<li><strong>Submit Button Text.</strong> Customize the copy on the submit button.</li>\n<li><strong>Spam Prevention.</strong> <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-build-a-spam-free-contact-form-without-captcha/\">Enable the anti-spam honeypot feature</a> to prevent spam race submissions and <a href=\"https://www.wpbeginner.com/wordpress-security/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">keep your website secure</a>. This feature is automatically enabled on all WordPress forms. If you decide to use another form of spam prevention, you can either unclick this option or continue using this feature with other spam prevention features such as recaptcha.</li>\n<li><strong>GDPR Enhancements.</strong> You can disable the storing of entry information and user details, such as IP addresses and user agents, in an effort to <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-create-gdpr-compliant-forms/\">comply with GDPR requirements</a>.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Click <strong>Save</strong>.</p>\n<h3>Step 3: Configure Your Video Release Form Notifications</h3>\n<p>Notifications are a great way to send an email whenever someone submits a video release form on your website.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-246852\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/WPForms-Notifications-Settings.png\" alt=\"WPForms Notifications Settings\" width=\"562\" height=\"228\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/WPForms-Notifications-Settings.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/WPForms-Notifications-Settings-300x122.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>In fact, unless you disable this feature, whenever someone submits a video release form on your site, you’ll get a notification about it.</p>\n<p>If you <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-use-smart-tags-in-wpforms/\">use smart tags</a>, you can also send a notification to people who fill out a video release form, letting them know you’ve received their form and will be in contact shortly if need be. This assures people their release form has gone through properly.</p>\n<p>You can also add important information to the notification about their video release form and the footage that was taken of them. For instance, you can mention where they might be able to view their footage when it airs. You can also include information about when and where the footage was taken so there’s no confusion later on.</p>\n<p>For help with this step, check out our documentation on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/setup-form-notification-wpforms/\">how to set up form notifications in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>You can send more than one notification when someone submits a video release form on your site. For example, you can send a notification to yourself, those that were recorded, and anyone on your production team that might need access to the release, and later the actual footage.</p>\n<p>For help doing this, check out our step by step tutorial on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-multiple-form-notifications-in-wordpress-forms/\">how to send multiple form notifications in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>Lastly, if you want to keep branding across your emails consistent, you can check out this guide on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-add-custom-header-image-in-your-wpforms-email-template/\">adding a custom header to your email template</a>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-211599\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Custom-Email-Header.jpg\" alt=\"Custom Email Header\" width=\"562\" height=\"314\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Custom-Email-Header.jpg 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Custom-Email-Header-300x168.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>This will give your video release form a professional touch and make people filling it out feel more at ease when releasing their rights to the video footage.</p>\n<h3>Step 4: Configure Your Video Release Form Confirmations</h3>\n<p>Form confirmations are messages that display to people once they submit a video release form on your website. They let people know that their form has gone through and offer you the chance to let them know what the next steps are.</p>\n<p>WPForms has three confirmation types:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Message.</strong> This is the default confirmation type in WPForms. When someone submits a video release form, a simple message confirmation will appear letting them know their form was received and is being processed.</li>\n<li><strong>Show Page.</strong> This confirmation type will take customers to a specific web page on your site thanking them. For help doing this, check out our tutorial on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-redirect-users-after-wordpress-form-submit/\">redirecting customers to a thank you page</a>.</li>\n<li><strong>Go to URL (Redirect).</strong> This option is used when you want to send people to a different website.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Let’s see <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/setup-form-confirmation-wpforms/\">how to set up a simple form confirmation in WPForms</a> so you can customize the message people will see when they fill out a video release form on your website.</p>\n<p>To start, click on the <strong>Confirmation</strong> tab in the Form Editor under <strong>Settings</strong>.</p>\n<p>Next, select the type of confirmation type you’d like to create. For this example, we’ll select <strong>Message</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-246854\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Confirmation-Message.png\" alt=\"Confirmation Message\" width=\"562\" height=\"290\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Confirmation-Message.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Confirmation-Message-300x155.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Then, customize the confirmation message to your liking and click <strong>Save</strong>.</p>\n<h3>Step 7: Add Your Video Release Form to Your Website</h3>\n<p>After you’ve created a video release form, you need to add it to your WordPress website.</p>\n<p>WPForms allows you to add your forms to many locations on your website, including your blog posts, pages, and even <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-add-a-contact-form-in-wordpress-sidebar-widget/\">sidebar widgets</a>.</p>\n<p>Let’s take a look at the most common post/page embed option.</p>\n<p>To start, create a new post or page in WordPress and then click on the <strong>Add Form</strong> button.</p>\n<p>Next, select your video release form in the modal popup and click <strong>Add Form</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-390991\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/add-video-release-form.png\" alt=\"add video release form\" width=\"562\" height=\"354\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/add-video-release-form.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/add-video-release-form-300x189.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Then, publish your post or page so your form will appear on your website.</p>\n<p>And there you have it! You now know how to create a video release form in WordPress.</p>\n<p>If you&#8217;re interested in using the video footage you&#8217;ve captured for promoting your business, be sure to check out this <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/the-ultimate-list-of-online-business-statistics/#video-marketing\">roundup of online business stats</a> and focus on the video marketing section.</p>\n<p>So, what are you waiting for? Get started with the most powerful <a href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WordPress forms plugin</a> today.</p>\n<p>And don’t forget, if you like this article, then please follow us on <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/wpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Facebook</a> and <a href=\"http://twitter.com/easywpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Twitter</a>.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-video-release-form-in-wordpress-step-by-step/\">How to Create a Video Release Form in WordPress (Step by Step)</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:86:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-video-release-form-in-wordpress-step-by-step/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:8;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:54:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:48:\"How to Create a Simple Contact Form in WordPress\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:69:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-simple-contact-form-in-wordpress/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:78:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-simple-contact-form-in-wordpress/#comments\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Thu, 28 Feb 2019 13:00:51 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:5:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:19:\"WordPress Tutorials\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:14:\"wordpress form\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:12:\"contact form\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:17:\"form notification\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:4;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:15:\"GDPR Form Field\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:27:\"https://wpforms.com/?p=1188\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:539:\"<p>Do you want to add a contact form to your WordPress website? As a site owner, you need to give your readers an easy way to get in touch with you. In this article, we’ll show you how to create a simple contact form in WordPress. Why Create a Simple Contact Form in WordPress? When [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-simple-contact-form-in-wordpress/\">How to Create a Simple Contact Form in WordPress</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:14:\"Lindsay Liedke\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:23449:\"<p>Do you want to add a contact form to your WordPress website? As a site owner, you need to give your readers an easy way to get in touch with you.</p>\n<p>In this article, we’ll show you how to create a simple contact form in WordPress.</p>\n<h3>Why Create a Simple Contact Form in WordPress?</h3>\n<p>When you&#8217;re a new website owner, you may wonder <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/contact-form-vs-email-address-which-is-better/\">whether to use a contact form or provide an email address</a> on your website.</p>\n<p>To help answer that question, here are the benefits of adding a contact form to your website:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Communication. </strong>Contact forms are a great way to allow your readers to quickly communicate with you.</li>\n<li><strong>Security. </strong>You keep your email safe from spammers. Since your contact form doesn’t show your email address, spammers can’t steal it.</li>\n<li><strong>Organization. </strong>With a contact form you can create <a href=\"https://optinmonster.com/101-email-subject-lines-your-subscribers-cant-resist/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">specific subject lines</a>, so people always know their emails are coming from you, and more importantly what the email is about.</li>\n<li><strong>Information. </strong>You control the information collected by adding only the fields you want site visitors to fill out on the form. This cuts down on the back and forth emails between you and a potential client.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Now let&#8217;s take a look at how to create a simple contact form in WordPress both by taking the WPForms Challenge and the traditional way you’ll create forms after knowing how to use WPForms.</p>\n<p>Here are some quick links to make things easier on you:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#wpforms-challenge\">Take the WPForms Challenge</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#create-contact-form\">Create a Simple Contact Form</a></li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"wpforms-challenge\">Take the WPForms Challenge – Create a Form in Under 5 Minutes</h3>\n<p>We created WPForms with the intention of it being the easiest, most beginner friendly form builder plugin in the market. And to prove that to you, we created the WPForms Challenge. We challenge all new users of WPForms to create their first form <strong>in under 5 minutes</strong> to show them just how simple this contact form solution is.</p>\n<p>The first thing you’ll need to do is install and activate the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/pricing/\">WPForms plugin</a>. For more details, see this step by step guide on <a title=\"Step by step guide on How to Install a WordPress Plugin\" href=\"http://www.wpbeginner.com/beginners-guide/step-by-step-guide-to-install-a-wordpress-plugin-for-beginners/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">how to install a plugin in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>Once activated, you’ll be prompted with WPForms’ setup wizard and the option to take the WPForms Challenge.</p>\n<p>Click <strong>Start the WPForms Challenge</strong> to get started.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-397505\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/start-the-wpforms-challenge.png\" alt=\"start the wpforms challenge\" width=\"562\" height=\"250\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/start-the-wpforms-challenge.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/start-the-wpforms-challenge-300x133.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p><strong>Step 1: Create Your First Form</strong></p>\n<p>You’ll be taken immediately to the WPForms form builder when you start the WPForms Challenge. This is where you’ll create your first form and configure all of its settings.</p>\n<p>You’ll see in the bottom right hand corner that there is a convenient checklist that will follow you as you create your form so you know you haven’t missed any steps. It also has a timer to show you how long you&#8217;ve spent creating your form.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-397499\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/challenge-checklist-and-timer.png\" alt=\"challenge checklist and timer\" width=\"562\" height=\"347\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/challenge-checklist-and-timer.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/challenge-checklist-and-timer-300x185.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>The first step in the challenge is to name your form. For our example, we’ll name our form Simple Contact Form.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-397502\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/name-your-form.png\" alt=\"name your form\" width=\"562\" height=\"173\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/name-your-form.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/name-your-form-300x92.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Click <strong>Done</strong> to move to the next step. You&#8217;ll see in the next step that the checklist has crossed out the Name Your Form step. This shows you that you’re on the right track.</p>\n<p><strong>Step 2: Customize Your Form Fields</strong></p>\n<p>Next it’s time to select a pre-designed template or use the blank template if you prefer to build your form from scratch. Since we’re creating a contact form, we’ll select the <strong>Simple Contact Form</strong> template.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-397503\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/select-a-template.png\" alt=\"select a template\" width=\"562\" height=\"459\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/select-a-template.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/select-a-template-300x245.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>When you click on the template you want to use, you’ll be taken to the part in the form builder that lets you add or remove form fields and customize the way they look and function. This part of form creation is optional.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-397498\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/add-form-fields-to-form.png\" alt=\"add form fields to form\" width=\"562\" height=\"454\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/add-form-fields-to-form.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/add-form-fields-to-form-300x242.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>We strive to make form building as simple and beginner friendly as possible. All of our templates have the basic form fields you’ll need without having to add or remove any fields.</p>\n<p>That said, we also strive to pack WPForms with powerful features so you can extend your form building capabilities and customize your forms to meet your needs.</p>\n<p>You can add additional fields to your contact form by dragging them from the left hand panel to the right hand panel.</p>\n<p>Then, click on the field to make any changes. You can also click on a form field and drag it to rearrange the order on your contact form.</p>\n<p>Once you’re finished customizing your form, click <strong>Done</strong>.</p>\n<p><strong>Step 3: Check Notification Settings</strong></p>\n<p>The next step in the WPForms Challenge deals with your form&#8217;s notification settings.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-397501\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/form-notifications.png\" alt=\"form notifications\" width=\"562\" height=\"362\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/form-notifications.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/form-notifications-300x193.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Notifications are a great way to send an email whenever a contact form is submitted on your website. In fact, unless you disable this feature, whenever someone submits a contact form on your site, you’ll get a notification about it.</p>\n<p>If you <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-use-smart-tags-in-wpforms/\">use smart tags</a>, you can also send a notification to the site visitor when they submit a contact form, letting them know you received their form and will be in contact shortly. This assures site visitors their form has gone through properly.</p>\n<p>For help with this step, check out our documentation on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/setup-form-notification-wpforms/\">how to set up form notifications in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>Adding to this, if you want to keep branding across your emails consistent, you can check out this guide on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-add-custom-header-image-in-your-wpforms-email-template/\">adding a custom header to your email template</a>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-211599\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Custom-Email-Header.jpg\" alt=\"Custom Email Header\" width=\"562\" height=\"314\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Custom-Email-Header.jpg 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Custom-Email-Header-300x168.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>When your form’s notifications are configured properly, click <strong>Done</strong>.</p>\n<p><strong>Step 4: Embed Your Simple Contact Form in a Page</strong></p>\n<p>The last step in the WPForms Challenge is embedding your simple contact form in a WordPress page.</p>\n<p>WPForms is Gutenberg ready and has its very own block to help make adding forms to your website a cinch. To add a form to your WordPress page, start by clicking the <strong>Add Block</strong> button and searching for WPForms.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-397506\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/wpforms-gutenberg-block.png\" alt=\"wpforms gutenberg block\" width=\"562\" height=\"553\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/wpforms-gutenberg-block.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/wpforms-gutenberg-block-300x295.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>When you click on WPForms, select your form from the dropdown menu and watch it automatically add to your WordPress page.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-397497\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/add-contact-form.png\" alt=\"add contact form\" width=\"562\" height=\"410\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/add-contact-form.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/add-contact-form-300x219.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>You can preview your form before publishing it on your website by clicking <strong>Preview</strong>, just like you would any time you wanted to check your content before pushing it live.</p>\n<p>When your form looks the way you want, and you’re ready to make it live on your website, finish up the WPForms Challenge by clicking <strong>Done</strong> one last time.</p>\n<p>If you’ve completed the challenge successfully, you’ll see a congratulations message with the amount of time it took you to create your first simple contact form.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-397500\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/finish-wpforms-challenge.png\" alt=\"finish wpforms challenge\" width=\"562\" height=\"428\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/finish-wpforms-challenge.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/finish-wpforms-challenge-300x228.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>If you want, you can even rate WPForms and share your story with others so they can see how easy it is to create a simple contact form in WordPress.</p>\n<p>Just don’t forget, you’ll need to click <strong>Publish</strong> for your form to go live on your site.</p>\n<div class=\"alert alert-info\">If you’re still using the Classic Editor, adding your form to your website is still simple. Click the <strong>Add Form</strong> button in the Visual Editor, select your form from the dropdown menu, and click <strong>Add Form</strong>. Then publish your page so your form appears on your site.</div>\n<h3 id=\"create-contact-form\">Create a Simple Contact Form</h3>\n<p>These step by step instructions are for those that don’t want to take the WPForms Challenge, or have already done it and want to know how to create a simple contact form in a more traditional way.</p>\n<p><strong>Step 1: Create a Simple Contact Form</strong></p>\n<p>The first thing you’ll need to do is install and activate the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/pricing/\">WPForms plugin</a>. For more details, see this step by step guide on <a title=\"Step by step guide on How to Install a WordPress Plugin\" href=\"http://www.wpbeginner.com/beginners-guide/step-by-step-guide-to-install-a-wordpress-plugin-for-beginners/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">how to install a plugin in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>Next, go to <strong>WPForms » Add New</strong> to create a new form.</p>\n<p>On the setup screen, name your form and select the Simple Contact Form template.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-397504\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/simple-contact-form-template.png\" alt=\"simple contact form template\" width=\"562\" height=\"365\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/simple-contact-form-template.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/simple-contact-form-template-300x195.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>WPForms will create a simple contact form.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-218831\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Simple-Contact-Form.png\" alt=\"Simple Contact Form\" width=\"562\" height=\"372\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Simple-Contact-Form.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Simple-Contact-Form-300x199.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Here, you can add additional fields to your contact form by dragging them from the left hand panel to the right hand panel.</p>\n<p>Then, click on the field to make any changes. You can also click on a form field and drag it to rearrange the order on your contact form.</p>\n<p>Once you’re done customizing your form, click <strong>Save</strong>.</p>\n<p>Now we’ll take a look at how to configure your simple contact form settings.</p>\n<p><strong>Step 2: Configure Your General Contact Form Settings</strong></p>\n<p>Go to <strong>Settings</strong> » <strong>General</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-218832\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/General-Settings.png\" alt=\"General Settings\" width=\"562\" height=\"439\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/General-Settings.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/General-Settings-300x234.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Here you can configure the following:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Form Name.</strong> Rename your form if you want to.</li>\n<li><strong>Form Description.</strong> Give your form name a description.</li>\n<li><strong>Submit Button Text.</strong> Customize the copy on the submit button.</li>\n<li><strong>Spam Prevention.</strong> <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-build-a-spam-free-contact-form-without-captcha/\">Enable the anti-spam honeypot feature</a> to prevent spambots from submitting forms. This feature is automatically enabled on all WordPress forms. If you decide to use another form of spam prevention, just unclick this option.</li>\n<li><strong>GDPR Enhancements.</strong> You can disable the storing of entry information and user details, such as IP addresses and user agents, in an effort to <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-create-gdpr-compliant-forms/\">comply with GDPR requirements</a>. In addition, check out our step by step instructions on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-add-a-gdpr-agreement-field-to-your-sites-forms/\">how to add a GDPR agreement field to your simple contact form</a>.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>When you’re done, click <strong>Save</strong>.</p>\n<p><strong>Step 3: Configure Your Contact Form’s Notifications</strong></p>\n<p>Notifications are a great way to send an email whenever a contact form is submitted on your website.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-218833\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Notifications.png\" alt=\"Notifications\" width=\"562\" height=\"228\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Notifications.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Notifications-300x122.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>In fact, unless you disable this feature, whenever someone submits a contact form on your site, you’ll get a notification about the contact form.</p>\n<p>If you <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-use-smart-tags-in-wpforms/\">use smart tags</a>, you can also send a notification to the site visitor when they submit a contact form, letting them know you received their form and will be in contact shortly. This assures site visitors their form has gone through properly.</p>\n<p>For help with this step, check out our documentation on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/setup-form-notification-wpforms/\">how to set up form notifications in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>Adding to this, if you want to keep branding across your emails consistent, you can check out this guide on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-add-custom-header-image-in-your-wpforms-email-template/\">adding a custom header to your email template</a>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-211599\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Custom-Email-Header.jpg\" alt=\"Custom Email Header\" width=\"562\" height=\"314\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Custom-Email-Header.jpg 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Custom-Email-Header-300x168.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p><strong>Step 4: Configure Your Contact Form Confirmations</strong></p>\n<p>Form confirmations are messages that display to site visitors once they submit a contact form on your website. They let people know that their form has been processed and offer you the chance to let them know the next steps.</p>\n<p>WPForms has three confirmation types to choose from:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Message.</strong> This is the default confirmation type in WPForms. When a site visitor submits a contact form, a simple message confirmation will appear letting them know their form was processed. Look here for some <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/form-success-message-ideas-to-boost-customer-happiness/\">great success messages</a> to help boost customer happiness.</li>\n<li><strong>Show Page.</strong> This confirmation type will take site visitors to a specific web page on your site thanking them for their form submission. For help doing this, check out our tutorial on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-redirect-users-after-wordpress-form-submit/\">redirecting customers to a thank you page</a>. In addition, be sure to check out our article on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/4-thank-you-page-examples-to-boost-customer-loyalty/\">creating effective Thank You pages</a> for boosting customer loyalty.</li>\n<li><strong>Go to URL (Redirect).</strong> This option is used when you want to send site visitors to a different website.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Let’s see how to set up a simple form confirmation in WPForms so you can customize the message site visitors will see when they get in touch with you using your site’s contact form.</p>\n<p>To start, click on the <strong>Confirmation</strong> tab in the Form Editor under <strong>Settings</strong>.</p>\n<p>Next, select the type of confirmation type you’d like to create. For this example, we’ll select <strong>Message</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-218836\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Confirmation-Message.png\" alt=\"Confirmation Message\" width=\"562\" height=\"290\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Confirmation-Message.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Confirmation-Message-300x155.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Then, customize the confirmation message to your liking, and click <strong>Save</strong>.</p>\n<p>For help with other confirmation types, see out documentation on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/setup-form-confirmation-wpforms/#redirect\">setting up form confirmations</a>.</p>\n<p>Now you’re ready to add your contact form to your website.</p>\n<p><strong>Step 5: Add Your Contact Form to Your Website</strong></p>\n<p>After you’ve created your simple contact form, you need to add it to your WordPress website.</p>\n<p>WPForms allows you to add your forms to many locations on your website, including your blog posts, pages, and even <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-add-a-contact-form-in-wordpress-sidebar-widget/\">sidebar widgets</a>.</p>\n<p>Let’s take a look at the most common post/page embed option.</p>\n<p>To start, create a new post or page in WordPress and then click on the <strong>Add Form</strong> button.</p>\n<p>Next, select your contact form in the modal popup and click <strong>Add Form</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-218834\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Add-Form-1.png\" alt=\"Add Form\" width=\"562\" height=\"326\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Add-Form-1.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Add-Form-1-300x174.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Then, publish your post or page so your contact form will appear on your website.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-218829\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Final-Contact-Form.png\" alt=\"Final Contact Form\" width=\"562\" height=\"334\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Final-Contact-Form.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Final-Contact-Form-300x178.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>And there you have it! You now know how to create a simple contact form in WordPress.</p>\n<p>If your website’s contact forms need multiple form fields, consider <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-multi-part-form-in-wordpress/\">creating a multi-part form</a> to prevent form fatigue and encourage people to finish filling your forms out. And don’t forget to <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/excellent-multi-page-form-examples-for-your-inspiration/\">check out our multi-page form examples</a> if you need some inspiration.</p>\n<p>And if you really want to get more information from your contact forms, without scaring away your visitors, check out these <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/web-form-hacks-to-unlock-customer-data/\">clever web form hacks to unlock hidden customer data</a>.</p>\n<p>So, what are you waiting for? Get started with the most powerful <a href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WordPress forms plugin</a> today.</p>\n<p>And don’t forget, if you like this article, then please follow us on <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/wpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Facebook</a> and <a href=\"http://twitter.com/easywpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Twitter</a>.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-simple-contact-form-in-wordpress/\">How to Create a Simple Contact Form in WordPress</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:74:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-simple-contact-form-in-wordpress/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:2:\"28\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:9;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:57:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:61:\"How to Create an Interactive Form in WordPress (the Easy Way)\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:80:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-an-interactive-form-in-wordpress-the-easy-way/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:89:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-an-interactive-form-in-wordpress-the-easy-way/#comments\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Wed, 27 Feb 2019 13:00:04 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:6:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:19:\"WordPress Tutorials\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:16:\"form abandonment\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:11:\"survey form\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:3;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:16:\"form conversions\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:4;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:26:\"conversational forms addon\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:5;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:16:\"interactive form\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:29:\"https://wpforms.com/?p=397397\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:582:\"<p>Are you looking for a way to create personal online forms and boost form completions at the same time? Giving your users a way to fill out forms as though they’re having a conversation is a great way to combat form abandonment. In this article, we’ll show you how to create an interactive form in [&#8230;]</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-an-interactive-form-in-wordpress-the-easy-way/\">How to Create an Interactive Form in WordPress (the Easy Way)</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:14:\"Lindsay Liedke\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:17570:\"<p>Are you looking for a way to create personal online forms and boost form completions at the same time? Giving your users a way to fill out forms as though they’re having a conversation is a great way to combat form abandonment.</p>\n<p>In this article, we’ll show you how to create an interactive form in WordPress.</p>\n<h3>What Are the Benefits of a Conversational Online Form?</h3>\n<p>There are many benefits to creating forms that mimic actual conversations:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Easier and faster to fill out, which boosts form completions</li>\n<li>Personal and engaging for users</li>\n<li>Can be filled out using only a keyboard, which increases form accessibility</li>\n<li>Interactive nature improves the user experience</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Up until now, there was no suitable Typeforms alternative in WordPress.</p>\n<p>That’s why our team worked hard to create <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/conversational-forms-addon/\">Conversational Forms by WPForms</a> to give your users an interactive form experience while improving form conversions.</p>\n<p>So, let’s see how to create a Typeforms style form in WordPress.</p>\n<p>But first, take a look at a conversation form demo to see what’s in store for you.</p>\n<p><a class=\"btn btn-block\" style=\"background-color: #659a17 !important; color: #fff !important; padding: 20px 25px !important; text-align: center; text-decoration: none; border-radius: 4px !important; -moz-border-radius: 4px !important; -webkit-border-radius: 4px !important; font-weight: bold;\" title=\"Click here to join our affiliate program\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/conversational-forms-demo/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Click here to see Conversational Form Demo</a></p>\n<h3>Step 1: Create a New Form in WordPress</h3>\n<p>The first thing you’ll need to do is install and activate the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/pricing/\">WPForms plugin</a>. For more details, see this step by step guide on <a title=\"Step by step guide on How to Install a WordPress Plugin\" href=\"http://www.wpbeginner.com/beginners-guide/step-by-step-guide-to-install-a-wordpress-plugin-for-beginners/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">how to install a plugin in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>Next, you’ll need to create a new form.</p>\n<p>You can create any number of online forms using WPForms and the <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/form-templates-pack-addon/\">Form Templates Pack addon</a>.</p>\n<p>For instance, you can create a:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-user-registration-form-in-wordpress/\">User Registration Form</a>:</strong> get all the information you need from users in a simple and fast way.</li>\n<li><strong>Event Planning Form:</strong> ask all the questions you need to throw an amazing event without exhausting your clients.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-a-job-application-form-in-wordpress/\">Job Application Form</a>:</strong> turn your long and sometimes complicated job application forms into simple and easy to digest forms.</li>\n<li><strong><a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/surveys-and-polls-addon/\">Survey Form</a>:</strong> stop overwhelming users with tons of survey questions. Instead, ask one question at a time and improve form completions and accuracy.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>For our example, we’ll create a simple survey form. For help with how to do this, check out this easy to follow tutorial on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/create-a-survey-form-in-wordpress-step-by-step/\">creating a survey form in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>If you want to see the survey form template in action, head over and check out our <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/demo/survey-form-demo/\">survey form demo</a>.</p>\n<p>You can add additional fields to your form by dragging them from the left hand panel to the right hand panel.</p>\n<p>Then, click on the field to make any changes. You can also click on a form field and drag it to rearrange the order on your online form.</p>\n<p>Here’s what our survey form looks like:</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-397402\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/conversational-survey-form-example.png\" alt=\"conversational survey form example\" width=\"562\" height=\"449\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/conversational-survey-form-example.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/conversational-survey-form-example-300x240.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Just remember, no matter which type of online form you create, you can give it a full-page conversational form layout.</p>\n<h3>Step 2: Install and Activate the Conversational Forms Addon</h3>\n<p>Once your WordPress form is ready, you’ll need to install and activate the WPForms <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/addons/conversational-forms-addon/\">Conversational Forms addon</a>.</p>\n<p>This addon is how you’ll be able to turn your newly created WordPress form into an interactive form.</p>\n<p>To do this, go to <strong>WPForms</strong> » <strong>Addons</strong> and find the one labeled <strong>Conversational Forms Addon</strong>.</p>\n<p>Click <strong>Install Addon</strong> and then <strong>Activate</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-397398\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/conversational-forms-addon.png\" alt=\"conversational forms addon\" width=\"562\" height=\"204\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/conversational-forms-addon.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/conversational-forms-addon-300x109.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>The Conversational Forms addon is now ready to use. But first, let’s take a quick look at the general form settings you might want to configure before creating your distraction free conversational form.</p>\n<h3>Step 3: Configure Your Form Settings</h3>\n<p>There are many settings to configure once you’ve customized your form to look the way you want it to.</p>\n<p><strong>General Settings</strong></p>\n<p>To start, go to <strong>Settings</strong> » <strong>General</strong>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-246850\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/WPForms-General-Settings.png\" alt=\"WPForms General Settings\" width=\"562\" height=\"443\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/WPForms-General-Settings.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/WPForms-General-Settings-300x236.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Here you can change things like your form’s name, description, and submit button copy.</p>\n<p>You can also <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-build-spam-free-wordpress-contact-forms-the-ultimate-guide/\">enable additional spam prevention features</a> to <a href=\"https://www.wpbeginner.com/wordpress-security/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">keep your website secure</a> from unwanted form submissions.</p>\n<p><strong>Form Notifications</strong></p>\n<p>Notifications are a great way to send an email whenever a form is submitted on your website.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-246852\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/WPForms-Notifications-Settings.png\" alt=\"WPForms Notifications Settings\" width=\"562\" height=\"228\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/WPForms-Notifications-Settings.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/WPForms-Notifications-Settings-300x122.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>In fact, unless you disable this feature, whenever someone submits a form on your site, you’ll get a notification about it.</p>\n<p>For help with this step, check out our documentation on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/setup-form-notification-wpforms/\">how to set up form notifications in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>If you need to send more than one notification, for example to yourself, a team member, and your site visitor, check out our step by step tutorial on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-multiple-form-notifications-in-wordpress-forms/\">how to send multiple form notifications in WordPress</a>.</p>\n<p>In addition, if you want to keep branding across your emails consistent, you can check out this guide on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-add-custom-header-image-in-your-wpforms-email-template/\">adding a custom header to your email template</a>.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-211599\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Custom-Email-Header.jpg\" alt=\"Custom Email Header\" width=\"562\" height=\"314\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Custom-Email-Header.jpg 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Custom-Email-Header-300x168.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p><strong>Form Confirmations</strong></p>\n<p>Form confirmations are messages that display to site visitors once they submit a form on your website. They let people know that their form has been processed and offer you the chance to let them know what the next steps are.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-246854\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Confirmation-Message.png\" alt=\"Confirmation Message\" width=\"562\" height=\"290\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Confirmation-Message.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Confirmation-Message-300x155.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>WPForms has three confirmation types:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Message.</strong>A simple message that displays once someone submits a form on your website thanking them and letting them know what the next steps are.</li>\n<li><strong>Show Page.</strong> Redirect users to another page on your website, such as a thank you page.</li>\n<li><strong>Go to URL (Redirect).</strong> Send site visitors to a different website.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>If you want to display different confirmations to site visitors based on their behavior, be sure to read up on <a href=\"https://wpforms.com/docs/how-to-create-conditional-form-confirmations/\">how to create conditional form confirmations</a>.</p>\n<p>Click <strong>Save</strong>.</p>\n<h3>Step 4: Configure Conversational Forms Settings</h3>\n<p>Now that you have your form’s general settings configured it’s time to configure your conversational form settings.</p>\n<p>To do this, go to <strong>Settings</strong> » <strong>Conversational Forms</strong> in the form builder and click on the <strong>Enable Conversational Form Mode</strong> checkbox.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-397404\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/enable-conversational-forms.png\" alt=\"enable conversational forms\" width=\"562\" height=\"260\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/enable-conversational-forms.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/enable-conversational-forms-300x139.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>When you do this, you’ll see a bunch of settings that you can customize to meet your needs.</p>\n<p><strong>Form Title and Message</strong></p>\n<p>To start, give your form a title that will display for your site visitors. This is good for letting people know what your form is all about and what action you want them to take while there.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-397401\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/conversational-forms-title.png\" alt=\"conversational forms title\" width=\"562\" height=\"189\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/conversational-forms-title.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/conversational-forms-title-300x101.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Next, you can add a short message for your site visitors to see. This gives you a chance to add some additional information so people know what to expect when they fill out your form.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-397399\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/conversational-forms-message.png\" alt=\"conversational forms message\" width=\"562\" height=\"239\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/conversational-forms-message.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/conversational-forms-message-300x128.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p><strong>Permalink</strong></p>\n<p>Whenever you enable conversational form mode for your online form, the Conversational Forms addon automatically creates a unique permalink for you.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-397400\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/conversational-forms-permalink.png\" alt=\"conversational forms permalink\" width=\"558\" height=\"94\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/conversational-forms-permalink.png 558w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/conversational-forms-permalink-300x51.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 558px) 100vw, 558px\" /></p>\n<p>You can change this permalink if you want, or leave it.</p>\n<p>Either way, this is the URL you’ll use in email campaigns, internal linking, and even social media posts when you want people to click on your conversational form link and visit your site.</p>\n<p><strong>Header Logo</strong></p>\n<p>The next thing you can do to customize your interactive form landing page is add a logo. Click on <strong>Upload Image</strong> and choose the image you want to add to your form landing page.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-379741\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/header-logo.png\" alt=\"header logo\" width=\"562\" height=\"180\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/header-logo.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/header-logo-300x96.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>You can also remove any WPForms branding by clicking the <strong>Hide WPForms Branding</strong> checkbox.</p>\n<p><strong>Color Schemes and Progress Bar</strong></p>\n<p>One of the best things about the WPForms Conversational Forms addon is that you can customize your interactive form landing page to have a color scheme that matches your company’s branding.</p>\n<p>The color scheme you choose will determine the background color of the your form’s landing page and the form’s buttons.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-397405\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/interactive-form-color-schemes.png\" alt=\"interactive form color schemes\" width=\"562\" height=\"333\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/interactive-form-color-schemes.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/interactive-form-color-schemes-300x178.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>To make things easy on you, we’ve given you several great color schemes to choose from that we know will look good no matter what.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-397410\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/color-schemes.png\" alt=\"color schemes\" width=\"562\" height=\"145\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/color-schemes.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/color-schemes-300x77.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>If you don’t like any of the pre-set colors, you can always use the color picker and choose a custom color.</p>\n<p>You also have two progress bar styles to choose from:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Percentage:</strong> show users in terms of percentage how far along they are while filling out your form.</li>\n<li><strong>Proportion:</strong> show users how many form fields they’ve completed, so they know how many questions are left to answer.</li>\n</ol>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-397406\" src=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/progress-bar-styles.png\" alt=\"progress bar styles\" width=\"562\" height=\"322\" srcset=\"https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/progress-bar-styles.png 562w, https://wpforms.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/progress-bar-styles-300x172.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 562px) 100vw, 562px\" /></p>\n<p>Once you’ve configured all your conversational form landing page’s settings, you can click the <strong>Preview Conversational Form</strong> button near the top to see how your form will look once it’s live.</p>\n<p>When everything looks the way you want it to, click <strong>Save</strong>.</p>\n<p>And that’s it! You now know how to create an interactive form in WordPress. Now people that have the unique URL or a link to your interactive form landing page will be able to view it and fill it out.</p>\n<p>If you’re looking for more ways to fight form abandonment, check out this article on <a href=\" https://wpforms.com/how-to-combat-order-form-abandonment-and-increase-your-sales/ \">combatting form abandonment to boost sales</a>.</p>\n<p>So, what are you waiting for? Get started with the most powerful <a href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WordPress forms plugin</a> today.</p>\n<p>And don’t forget, if you like this article, then please follow us on <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/wpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Facebook</a> and <a href=\"http://twitter.com/easywpforms\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\">Twitter</a>.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-an-interactive-form-in-wordpress-the-easy-way/\">How to Create an Interactive Form in WordPress (the Easy Way)</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://wpforms.com\">WPForms</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:85:\"https://wpforms.com/how-to-create-an-interactive-form-in-wordpress-the-easy-way/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"2\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}}}s:27:\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\";a:1:{s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:3:{s:4:\"href\";s:25:\"h